[1] "To the Senate and House of Representatives:\r\n\r\nThe Nation continues to enjoy noteworthy prosperity. Such prosperity is\r\nof course primarily due to the high individual average of our\r\ncitizenship, taken together with our great natural resources; but an\r\nimportant factor therein is the working of our long-continued\r\ngovernmental policies. The people have emphatically expressed their\r\napproval of the principles underlying these policies, and their desire\r\nthat these principles be kept substantially unchanged, although of\r\ncourse applied in a progressive spirit to meet changing conditions.\r\n\r\nThe enlargement of scope of the functions of the National Government\r\nrequired by our development as a nation involves, of course, increase of\r\nexpense; and the period of prosperity through which the country is\r\npassing justifies expenditures for permanent improvements far greater\r\nthan would be wise in hard times. Battle ships and forts, public\r\nbuildings, and improved waterways are investments which should be made\r\nwhen we have the money; but abundant revenues and a large surplus always\r\ninvite extravagance, and constant care should be taken to guard against\r\nunnecessary increase of the ordinary expenses of government. The cost of\r\ndoing Government business should be regulated with the same rigid\r\nscrutiny as the cost of doing a private business.\r\n\r\nIn the vast and complicated mechanism of our modern civilized life the\r\ndominant note is the note of industrialism; and the relations of capital\r\nand labor, and especially of organized capital and organized labor, to\r\neach other and to the public at large come second in importance only to\r\nthe intimate questions of family life. Our peculiar form of government,\r\nwith its sharp division of authority between the Nation and the several\r\nStates, has been on the whole far more advantageous to our development\r\nthan a more strongly centralized government. But it is undoubtedly\r\nresponsible for much of the difficulty of meeting with adequate\r\nlegislation the new problems presented by the total change in industrial\r\nconditions on this continent during the last half century. In actual\r\npractice it has proved exceedingly difficult, and in many cases\r\nimpossible, to get unanimity of wise action among the various States on\r\nthese subjects. From the very nature of the case this is especially true\r\nof the laws affecting the employment of capital in huge masses.\r\n\r\nWith regard to labor the problem is no less important, but it is\r\nsimpler. As long as the States retain the primary control of the police\r\npower the circumstances must be altogether extreme which require\r\ninterference by the Federal authorities, whether in the way of\r\nsafeguarding the rights of labor or in the way of seeing that wrong is\r\nnot done by unruly persons who shield themselves behind the name of\r\nlabor. If there is resistance to the Federal courts, interference with\r\nthe mails, or interstate commerce, or molestation of Federal property,\r\nor if the State authorities in some crisis which they are unable to face\r\ncall for help, then the Federal Government may interfere; but though\r\nsuch interference may be caused by a condition of things arising out of\r\ntrouble connected with some question of labor, the interference itself\r\nsimply takes the form of restoring order without regard to the questions\r\nwhich have caused the breach of order--for to keep order is a primary\r\nduty and in a time of disorder and violence all other questions sink\r\ninto abeyance until order has been restored. In the District of Columbia\r\nand in the Territories the Federal law covers the entire field of\r\ngovernment; but the labor question is only acute in populous centers of\r\ncommerce, manufactures, or mining. Nevertheless, both in the enactment\r\nand in the enforcement of law the Federal Government within its\r\nrestricted sphere should set an example to the State governments,\r\nespecially in a matter so vital as this affecting labor. I believe that\r\nunder modern industrial conditions it is often necessary, and even where\r\nnot necessary it is yet often wise, that there should be organization of\r\nlabor in order better to secure the rights of the individual\r\nwage-worker. All encouragement should be given to any such organization\r\nso long as it is conducted with a due and decent regard for the rights\r\nof others. There are in this country some labor unions which have\r\nhabitually, and other labor unions which have often, been among the most\r\neffective agents in working for good citizenship and for uplifting the\r\ncondition of those whose welfare should be closest to our hearts. But\r\nwhen any labor union seeks improper ends, or seeks to achieve proper\r\nends by improper means, all good citizens and more especially all\r\nhonorable public servants must oppose the wrongdoing as resolutely as\r\nthey would oppose the wrongdoing of any great corporation. Of course any\r\nviolence, brutality, or corruption, should not for one moment be\r\ntolerated. Wage-workers have an entire right to organize and by all\r\npeaceful and honorable means to endeavor to persuade their fellows to\r\njoin with them in organizations. They have a legal right, which,\r\naccording to circumstances, may or may not be a moral right, to refuse\r\nto work in company with men who decline to join their organizations.\r\nThey have under no circumstances the right to commit violence upon\r\nthese, whether capitalists or wage-workers, who refuse to support their\r\norganizations, or who side with those with whom they are at odds; for\r\nmob rule is intolerable in any form.\r\n\r\nThe wage-workers are peculiarly entitled to the protection and the\r\nencouragement of the law. From the very nature of their occupation\r\nrailroad men, for instance, are liable to be maimed in doing the\r\nlegitimate work of their profession, unless the railroad companies are\r\nrequired by law to make ample provision for their safety. The\r\nAdministration has been zealous in enforcing the existing law for this\r\npurpose. That law should be amended and strengthened. Wherever the\r\nNational Government has power there should be a stringent employer's\r\nliability law, which should apply to the Government itself where the\r\nGovernment is an employer of labor.\r\n\r\nIn my Message to the Fifty-seventh Congress, at its second session, I\r\nurged the passage of an employer's liability law for the District of\r\nColumbia. I now renew that recommendation, and further recommend that\r\nthe Congress appoint a commission to make a comprehensive study of\r\nemployer's liability with the view of extending the provisions of a\r\ngreat and constitutional law to all employments within the scope of\r\nFederal power.\r\n\r\nThe Government has recognized heroism upon the water, and bestows medals\r\nof honor upon those persons who by extreme and heroic daring have\r\nendangered their lives in saving, or endeavoring to save, lives from the\r\nperils of the sea in the waters over which the United States has\r\njurisdiction, or upon an American vessel. This recognition should be\r\nextended to cover cases of conspicuous bravery and self-sacrifice in the\r\nsaving of life in private employments under the jurisdiction of the\r\nUnited States, and particularly in the land commerce of the Nation.\r\n\r\nThe ever-increasing casualty list upon our railroads is a matter of\r\ngrave public concern, and urgently calls for action by the Congress. In\r\nthe matter of speed and comfort of railway travel our railroads give at\r\nleast as good service as those of any other nation, and there is no\r\nreason why this service should not also be as safe as human ingenuity\r\ncan make it. Many of our leading roads have been foremost in the\r\nadoption of the most approved safeguards for the protection of travelers\r\nand employees, yet the list of clearly avoidable accidents continues\r\nunduly large. The passage of a law requiring the adoption of a\r\nblock-signal system has been proposed to the Congress. I earnestly\r\nconcur in that recommendation, and would also point out to the Congress\r\nthe urgent need of legislation in the interest of the public safety\r\nlimiting the hours of labor for railroad employees in train service upon\r\nrailroads engaged in interstate commerce, and providing that only\r\ntrained and experienced persons be employed in positions of\r\nresponsibility connected with the operation of trains. Of course nothing\r\ncan ever prevent accidents caused by human weakness or misconduct; and\r\nthere should be drastic punishment for any railroad employee, whether\r\nofficer or man, who by issuance of wrong orders or by disobedience of\r\norders causes disaster. The law of 1901, requiring interstate railroads\r\nto make monthly reports of all accidents to passengers and employees on\r\nduty, should also be amended so as to empower the Government to make a\r\npersonal investigation, through proper officers, of all accidents\r\ninvolving loss of life which seem to require investigation, with a\r\nrequirement that the results of such investigation be made public.\r\n\r\nThe safety-appliance law, as amended by the act of March 2, 1903, has\r\nproved beneficial to railway employees, and in order that its provisions\r\nmay be properly carried out, the force of inspectors provided for by\r\nappropriation should be largely increased. This service is analogous to\r\nthe Steamboat-Inspection Service, and deals with even more important\r\ninterests. It has passed the experimental stage and demonstrated its\r\nutility, and should receive generous recognition by the Congress.\r\n\r\nThere is no objection to employees of the Government forming or\r\nbelonging to unions; but the Government can neither discriminate for nor\r\ndiscriminate against nonunion men who are in its employment, or who seek\r\nto be employed under it. Moreover, it is a very grave impropriety for\r\nGovernment employees to band themselves together for the purpose of\r\nextorting improperly high salaries from the Government. Especially is\r\nthis true of those within the classified service. The letter carriers,\r\nboth municipal and rural, are as a whole an excellent body of public\r\nservants. They should be amply paid. But their payment must be obtained\r\nby arguing their claims fairly and honorably before the Congress, and\r\nnot by banding together for the defeat of those Congressmen who refuse\r\nto give promises which they can not in conscience give. The\r\nAdministration has already taken steps to prevent and punish abuses of\r\nthis nature; but it will be wise for the Congress to supplement this\r\naction by legislation.\r\n\r\nMuch can be done by the Government in labor matters merely by giving\r\npublicity to certain conditions. The Bureau of Labor has done excellent\r\nwork of this kind in many different directions. I shall shortly lay\r\nbefore you in a special message the full report of the investigation of\r\nthe Bureau of Labor into the Colorado mining strike, as this was a\r\nstrike in which certain very evil forces, which are more or less at work\r\neverywhere under the conditions of modern industrialism, became\r\nstartlingly prominent. It is greatly to be wished that the Department of\r\nCommerce and Labor, through the Labor Bureau, should compile and arrange\r\nfor the Congress a list of the labor laws of the various States, and\r\nshould be given the means to investigate and report to the Congress upon\r\nthe labor conditions in the manufacturing and mining regions throughout\r\nthe country, both as to wages, as to hours of labor, as to the labor of\r\nwomen and children, and as to the effect in the various labor centers of\r\nimmigration from abroad. In this investigation especial attention should\r\nbe paid to the conditions of child labor and child-labor legislation in\r\nthe several States. Such an investigation must necessarily take into\r\naccount many of the problems with which this question of child labor is\r\nconnected. These problems can be actually met, in most cases, only by\r\nthe States themselves; but the lack of proper legislation in one State\r\nin such a matter as child labor often renders it excessively difficult\r\nto establish protective restriction upon the work in another State\r\nhaving the same industries, so that the worst tends to drag down the\r\nbetter. For this reason, it would be well for the Nation at least to\r\nendeavor to secure comprehensive information as to the conditions of\r\nlabor of children in the different States. Such investigation and\r\npublication by the National Government would tend toward the securing of\r\napproximately uniform legislation of the proper character among the\r\nseveral States.\r\n\r\nWhen we come to deal with great corporations the need for the Government\r\nto act directly is far greater than in the case of labor, because great\r\ncorporations can become such only by engaging in interstate commerce,\r\nand interstate commerce is peculiarly the field of the General\r\nGovernment. It is an absurdity to expect to eliminate the abuses in\r\ngreat corporations by State action. It is difficult to be patient with\r\nan argument that such matters should be left to the States because more\r\nthan one State pursues the policy of creating on easy terms corporations\r\nwhich are never operated within that State at all, but in other States\r\nwhose laws they ignore. The National Government alone can deal\r\nadequately with these great corporations. To try to deal with them in an\r\nintemperate, destructive, or demagogic spirit would, in all probability,\r\nmean that nothing whatever would be accomplished, and, with absolute\r\ncertainty, that if anything were accomplished it would be of a harmful\r\nnature. The American people need to continue to show the very qualities\r\nthat they have shown--that is, moderation, good sense, the earnest\r\ndesire to avoid doing any damage, and yet the quiet determination to\r\nproceed, step by step, without halt and without hurry, in eliminating or\r\nat least in minimizing whatever of mischief or evil there is to\r\ninterstate commerce in the conduct of great corporations. They are\r\nacting in no spirit of hostility to wealth, either individual or\r\ncorporate. They are not against the rich man any more than against the\r\npoor man. On the contrary, they are friendly alike toward rich man and\r\ntoward poor man, provided only that each acts in a spirit of justice and\r\ndecency toward his fellows. Great corporations are necessary, and only\r\nmen of great and singular mental power can manage such corporations\r\nsuccessfully, and such men must have great rewards. But these\r\ncorporations should be managed with due regard to the interest of the\r\npublic as a whole. Where this can be done under the present laws it must\r\nbe done. Where these laws come short others should be enacted to\r\nsupplement them.\r\n\r\nYet we must never forget the determining factor in every kind of work,\r\nof head or hand, must be the man's own good sense, courage, and\r\nkindliness. More important than any legislation is the gradual growth of\r\na feeling of responsibility and forbearance among capitalists, and\r\nwage-workers alike; a feeling of respect on the part of each man for the\r\nrights of others; a feeling of broad community of interest, not merely\r\nof capitalists among themselves, and of wage-workers among themselves,\r\nbut of capitalists and wage-workers in their relations to each other,\r\nand of both in their relations to their fellows who with them make up\r\nthe body politic. There are many captains of industry, many labor\r\nleaders, who realize this. A recent speech by the president of one of\r\nour great railroad systems to the employees of that system contains\r\nsound common sense. It rims in part as follows:\r\n\r\n\"It is my belief we can better serve each other, better understand the\r\nman as well as his business, when meeting face to face, exchanging\r\nviews, and realizing from personal contact we serve but one interest,\r\nthat of our mutual prosperity.\r\n\r\n\"Serious misunderstandings can not occur where personal good will exists\r\nand opportunity for personal explanation is present.\r\n\r\n\"In my early business life I had experience with men of affairs of a\r\ncharacter to make me desire to avoid creating a like feeling of\r\nresentment to myself and the interests in my charge, should fortune ever\r\nplace me in authority, and I am solicitous of a measure of confidence on\r\nthe part of the public and our employees that I shall hope may be\r\nwarranted by the fairness and good fellowship I intend shall prevail in\r\nour relationship.\r\n\r\n\"But do not feel I am disposed to grant unreasonable requests, spend the\r\nmoney of our company unnecessarily or without value received, nor expect\r\nthe days of mistakes are disappearing, or that cause for complaint will\r\nnot continually occur; simply to correct such abuses as may be\r\ndiscovered, to better conditions as fast as reasonably may be expected,\r\nconstantly striving, with varying success, for that improvement we all\r\ndesire, to convince you there is a force at work in the right direction,\r\nall the time making progress--is the disposition with which I have come\r\namong you, asking your good will and encouragement.\r\n\r\n\"The day has gone by when a corporation can be handled successfully in\r\ndefiance of the public will, even though that will be unreasonable and\r\nwrong. A public may be led, but not driven, and I prefer to go with it\r\nand shape or modify, in a measure, its opinion, rather than be swept\r\nfrom my bearings, with loss to myself and the interests in my charge.\r\n\r\n\"Violent prejudice exists towards corporate activity and capital today,\r\nmuch of it founded in reason, more in apprehension, and a large measure\r\nis due to the personal traits of arbitrary, unreasonable, incompetent,\r\nand offensive men in positions of authority. The accomplishment of\r\nresults by indirection, the endeavor to thwart the intention, if not the\r\nexpressed letter of the law (the will of the people), a disregard of the\r\nrights of others, a disposition to withhold what is due, to force by\r\nmain strength or inactivity a result not justified, depending upon the\r\nweakness of the claimant and his indisposition to become involved in\r\nlitigation, has created a sentiment harmful in the extreme and a\r\ndisposition to consider anything fair that gives gain to the individual\r\nat the expense of the company.\r\n\r\n\"If corporations are to continue to do the world's work, as they are\r\nbest fitted to, these qualities in their representatives that have\r\nresulted in the present prejudice against them must be relegated to the\r\nbackground. The corporations must come out into the open and see and be\r\nseen. They must take the public into their confidence and ask for what\r\nthey want, and no more, and be prepared to explain satisfactorily what\r\nadvantage will accrue to the public if they are given their desires; for\r\nthey are permitted to exist not that they may make money solely, but\r\nthat they may effectively serve those from whom they derive their power.\r\n\r\n\"Publicity, and not secrecy, will win hereafter, and laws be construed\r\nby their intent and not by their letter, otherwise public utilities will\r\nbe owned and operated by the public which created them, even though the\r\nservice be less efficient and the result less satisfactory from a\r\nfinancial standpoint.\"\r\n\r\nThe Bureau of Corporations has made careful preliminary investigation of\r\nmany important corporations. It will make a special report on the beef\r\nindustry.\r\n\r\nThe policy of the Bureau is to accomplish the purposes of its creation\r\nby co-operation, not antagonism; by making constructive legislation, not\r\ndestructive prosecution, the immediate object of its inquiries; by\r\nconservative investigation of law and fact, and by refusal to issue\r\nincomplete and hence necessarily inaccurate reports. Its policy being\r\nthus one of open inquiry into, and not attack upon, business, the Bureau\r\nhas been able to gain not only the confidence, but, better still, the\r\ncooperation of men engaged in legitimate business.\r\n\r\nThe Bureau offers to the Congress the means of getting at the cost of\r\nproduction of our various great staples of commerce.\r\n\r\nOf necessity the careful investigation of special corporations will\r\nafford the Commissioner knowledge of certain business facts, the\r\npublication of which might be an improper infringement of private\r\nrights. The method of making public the results of these investigations\r\naffords, under the law, a means for the protection of private rights.\r\nThe Congress will have all facts except such as would give to another\r\ncorporation information which would injure the legitimate business of a\r\ncompetitor and destroy the incentive for individual superiority and\r\nthrift.\r\n\r\nThe Bureau has also made exhaustive examinations into the legal\r\ncondition under which corporate business is carried on in the various\r\nStates; into all judicial decisions on the subject; and into the various\r\nsystems of corporate taxation in use. I call special attention to the\r\nreport of the chief of the Bureau; and I earnestly ask that the Congress\r\ncarefully consider the report and recommendations of the Commissioner on\r\nthis subject.\r\n\r\nThe business of insurance vitally affects the great mass of the people\r\nof the United States and is national and not local in its application.\r\nIt involves a multitude of transactions among the people of the\r\ndifferent States and between American companies and foreign governments.\r\nI urge that the Congress carefully consider whether the power of the\r\nBureau of Corporations can not constitutionally be extended to cover\r\ninterstate transactions in insurance.\r\n\r\nAbove all else, we must strive to keep the highways of commerce open to\r\nall on equal terms; and to do this it is necessary to put a complete\r\nstop to all rebates. Whether the shipper or the railroad is to blame\r\nmakes no difference; the rebate must be stopped, the abuses of the\r\nprivate car and private terminal-track and side-track systems must be\r\nstopped, and the legislation of the Fifty-eighth Congress which declares\r\nit to be unlawful for any person or corporation to offer, grant, give,\r\nsolicit, accept, or receive any rebate, concession, or discrimination in\r\nrespect of the transportation of any property in interstate or foreign\r\ncommerce whereby such property shall by any device whatever be\r\ntransported at a less rate than that named in the tariffs published by\r\nthe carrier must be enforced. For some time after the enactment of the\r\nAct to Regulate Commerce it remained a mooted question whether that act\r\nconferred upon the Interstate Commerce Commission the power, after it\r\nhad found a challenged rate to be unreasonable, to declare what\r\nthereafter should, prima facie, be the reasonable maximum rate for the\r\ntransportation in dispute. The Supreme Court finally resolved that\r\nquestion in the negative, so that as the law now stands the Commission\r\nsimply possess the bare power to denounce a particular rate as\r\nunreasonable. While I am of the opinion that at present it would be\r\nundesirable, if it were not impracticable, finally to clothe the\r\nCommission with general authority to fix railroad rates, I do believe\r\nthat, as a fair security to shippers, the Commission should be vested\r\nwith the power, where a given rate has been challenged and after full\r\nhearing found to be unreasonable, to decide, subject to judicial review,\r\nwhat shall be a reasonable rate to take its place; the ruling of the\r\nCommission to take effect immediately, and to obtain unless and until it\r\nis reversed by the court of review. The Government must in increasing\r\ndegree supervise and regulate the workings of the railways engaged in\r\ninterstate commerce; and such increased supervision is the only\r\nalternative to an increase of the present evils on the one hand or a\r\nstill more radical policy on the other. In my judgment the most\r\nimportant legislative act now needed as regards the regulation of\r\ncorporations is this act to confer on the Interstate Commerce Commission\r\nthe power to revise rates and regulations, the revised rate to at once\r\ngo into effect, and stay in effect unless and until the court of review\r\nreverses it.\r\n\r\nSteamship companies engaged in interstate commerce and protected in our\r\ncoastwise trade should be held to a strict observance of the interstate\r\ncommerce act.\r\n\r\nIn pursuing the set plan to make the city of Washington an example to\r\nother American municipalities several points should be kept in mind by\r\nthe legislators. In the first place, the people of this country should\r\nclearly understand that no amount of industrial prosperity, and above\r\nall no leadership in international industrial competition, can in any\r\nway atone for the sapping of the vitality of those who are usually\r\nspoken of as the working classes. The farmers, the mechanics, the\r\nskilled and unskilled laborers, the small shop keepers, make up the bulk\r\nof the population of any country; and upon their well-being, generation\r\nafter generation, the well-being of the country and the race depends.\r\nRapid development in wealth and industrial leadership is a good thing,\r\nbut only if it goes hand in hand with improvement, and not\r\ndeterioration, physical and moral. The over-crowding of cities and the\r\ndraining of country districts are unhealthy and even dangerous symptoms\r\nin our modern life. We should not permit overcrowding in cities. In\r\ncertain European cities it is provided by law that the population of\r\ntowns shall not be allowed to exceed a very limited density for a given\r\narea, so that the increase in density must be continually pushed back\r\ninto a broad zone around the center of the town, this zone having great\r\navenues or parks within it. The death-rate statistics show a terrible\r\nincrease in mortality, and especially in infant mortality, in\r\novercrowded tenements. The poorest families in tenement houses live in\r\none room, and it appears that in these one-room tenements the average\r\ndeath rate for a number of given cities at home and abroad is about\r\ntwice what it is in a two-room tenement, four times what it is in a\r\nthree-room tenement, and eight times what it is in a tenement consisting\r\nof four rooms or over. These figures vary somewhat for different cities,\r\nbut they approximate in each city those given above; and in all cases\r\nthe increase of mortality, and especially of infant mortality, with the\r\ndecrease in the number of rooms used by the family and with the\r\nconsequent overcrowding is startling. The slum exacts a heavy total of\r\ndeath from those who dwell therein; and this is the case not merely in\r\nthe great crowded slums of high buildings in New York and Chicago, but\r\nin the alley slums of Washington. In Washington people can not afford to\r\nignore the harm that this causes. No Christian and civilized community\r\ncan afford to show a happy-go-lucky lack of concern for the youth of\r\nto-day; for, if so, the community will have to pay a terrible penalty of\r\nfinancial burden and social degradation in the to-morrow. There should\r\nbe severe child-labor and factory-inspection laws. It is very desirable\r\nthat married women should not work in factories. The prime duty of the\r\nman is to work, to be the breadwinner; the prime duty of the woman is to\r\nbe the mother, the housewife. All questions of tariff and finance sink\r\ninto utter insignificance when compared with the tremendous, the vital\r\nimportance of trying to shape conditions so that these two duties of the\r\nman and of the woman can be fulfilled under reasonably favorable\r\ncircumstances. If a race does not have plenty of children, or if the\r\nchildren do not grow up, or if when they grow up they are unhealthy in\r\nbody and stunted or vicious in mind, then that race is decadent, and no\r\nheaping up of wealth, no splendor of momentary material prosperity, can\r\navail in any degree as offsets.  The Congress has the same power of\r\nlegislation for the District of Columbia which the State legislatures\r\nhave for the various States. The problems incident to our highly complex\r\nmodern industrial civilization, with its manifold and perplexing\r\ntendencies both for good and for evil, are far less sharply accentuated\r\nin the city of Washington than in most other cities. For this very\r\nreason it is easier to deal with the various phases of these problems in\r\nWashington, and the District of Columbia government should be a model\r\nfor the other municipal governments of the Nation, in all such matters\r\nas supervision of the housing of the poor, the creation of small parks\r\nin the districts inhabited by the poor, in laws affecting labor, in laws\r\nproviding for the taking care of the children, in truant laws, and in\r\nproviding schools.\r\n\r\nIn the vital matter of taking care of children, much advantage could be\r\ngained by a careful study of what has been accomplished in such States\r\nas Illinois and Colorado by the juvenile courts. The work of the\r\njuvenile court is really a work of character building. It is now\r\ngenerally recognized that young boys and young girls who go wrong should\r\nnot be treated as criminals, not even necessarily as needing\r\nreformation, but rather as needing to have their characters formed, and\r\nfor this end to have them tested and developed by a system of probation.\r\nMuch admirable work has been done in many of our Commonwealths by\r\nearnest men and women who have made a special study of the needs of\r\nthose classes of children which furnish the greatest number of juvenile\r\noffenders, and therefore the greatest number of adult offenders; and by\r\ntheir aid, and by profiting by the experiences of the different States\r\nand cities in these matters, it would be easy to provide a good code for\r\nthe District of Columbia.\r\n\r\nSeveral considerations suggest the need for a systematic investigation\r\ninto and improvement of housing conditions in Washington. The hidden\r\nresidential alleys are breeding grounds of vice and disease, and should\r\nbe opened into minor streets. For a number of years influential citizens\r\nhave joined with the District Commissioners in the vain endeavor to\r\nsecure laws permitting the condemnation of insanitary dwellings. The\r\nlocal death rates, especially from preventable diseases, are so unduly\r\nhigh as to suggest that the exceptional wholesomeness of Washington's\r\nbetter sections is offset by bad conditions in her poorer neighborhoods.\r\nA special \"Commission on Housing and Health Conditions in the National\r\nCapital\" would not only bring about the reformation of existing evils,\r\nbut would also formulate an appropriate building code to protect the\r\ncity from mammoth brick tenements and other evils which threaten to\r\ndevelop here as they have in other cities. That the Nation's Capital\r\nshould be made a model for other municipalities is an ideal which\r\nappeals to all patriotic citizens everywhere, and such a special\r\nCommission might map out and organize the city's future development in\r\nlines of civic social service, just as Major L'Enfant and the recent\r\nPark Commission planned the arrangement of her streets and parks.\r\n\r\nIt is mortifying to remember that Washington has no compulsory school\r\nattendance law and that careful inquiries indicate the habitual absence\r\nfrom school of some twenty per cent of all children between the ages of\r\neight and fourteen. It must be evident to all who consider the problems\r\nof neglected child life or the benefits of compulsory education in other\r\ncities that one of the most urgent needs of the National Capital is a\r\nlaw requiring the school attendance of all children, this law to be\r\nenforced by attendance agents directed by the board of education.\r\n\r\nPublic play grounds are necessary means for the development of wholesome\r\ncitizenship in modern cities. It is important that the work inaugurated\r\nhere through voluntary efforts should be taken up and extended through\r\nCongressional appropriation of funds sufficient to equip and maintain\r\nnumerous convenient small play grounds upon land which can be secured\r\nwithout purchase or rental. It is also desirable that small vacant\r\nplaces be purchased and reserved as small-park play grounds in densely\r\nsettled sections of the city which now have no public open spaces and\r\nare destined soon to be built up solidly. All these needs should be met\r\nimmediately. To meet them would entail expenses; but a corresponding\r\nsaving could be made by stopping the building of streets and levelling\r\nof ground for purposes largely speculative in outlying parts of the\r\ncity.\r\n\r\nThere are certain offenders, whose criminality takes the shape of\r\nbrutality and cruelty towards the weak, who need a special type of\r\npunishment. The wife-beater, for example, is inadequately punished by\r\nimprisonment; for imprisonment may often mean nothing to him, while it\r\nmay cause hunger and want to the wife and children who have been the\r\nvictims of his brutality. Probably some form of corporal punishment\r\nwould be the most adequate way of meeting this kind of crime.\r\n\r\nThe Department of Agriculture has grown into an educational institution\r\nwith a faculty of two thousand specialists making research into all the\r\nsciences of production. The Congress appropriates, directly and\r\nindirectly, six millions of dollars annually to carry on this work. It\r\nreaches every State and Territory in the Union and the islands of the\r\nsea lately come under our flag. Co-operation is had with the State\r\nexperiment stations, and with many other institutions and individuals.\r\nThe world is carefully searched for new varieties of grains, fruits,\r\ngrasses, vegetables, trees, and shrubs, suitable to various localities\r\nin our country; and marked benefit to our producers has resulted.\r\n\r\nThe activities of our age in lines of research have reached the tillers\r\nof the soil and inspired them with ambition to know more of the\r\nprinciples that govern the forces of nature with which they have to\r\ndeal. Nearly half of the people of this country devote their energies to\r\ngrowing things from the soil. Until a recent date little has been done\r\nto prepare these millions for their life work. In most lines of human\r\nactivity college-trained men are the leaders. The farmer had no\r\nopportunity for special training until the Congress made provision for\r\nit forty years ago. During these years progress has been made and\r\nteachers have been prepared. Over five thousand students are in\r\nattendance at our State agricultural colleges. The Federal Government\r\nexpends ten millions of dollars annually toward this education and for\r\nresearch in Washington and in the several States and Territories. The\r\nDepartment of Agriculture has given facilities for post-graduate work to\r\nfive hundred young men during the last seven years, preparing them for\r\nadvance lines of work in the Department and in the State institutions.\r\n\r\nThe facts concerning meteorology and its relations to plant and animal\r\nlife are being systematically inquired into. Temperature and moisture\r\nare controlling factors in all agricultural operations. The seasons of\r\nthe cyclones of the Caribbean Sea and their paths are being forecasted\r\nwith increasing accuracy. The cold winds that come from the north are\r\nanticipated and their times and intensity told to farmers, gardeners,\r\nand fruiterers in all southern localities.\r\n\r\nWe sell two hundred and fifty million dollars' worth of animals and\r\nanimal products to foreign countries every year, in addition to\r\nsupplying our own people more cheaply and abundantly than any other\r\nnation is able to provide for its people. Successful manufacturing\r\ndepends primarily on cheap food, which accounts to a considerable extent\r\nfor our growth in this direction. The Department of Agriculture, by\r\ncareful inspection of meats, guards the health of our people and gives\r\nclean bills of health to deserving exports; it is prepared to deal\r\npromptly with imported diseases of animals, and maintain the excellence\r\nof our flocks and herds in this respect. There should be an annual\r\ncensus of the live stock of the Nation.\r\n\r\nWe sell abroad about six hundred million dollars' worth of plants and\r\ntheir products every year. Strenuous efforts are being made to import\r\nfrom foreign countries such grains as are suitable to our varying\r\nlocalities. Seven years ago we bought three-fourths of our rice; by\r\nhelping the rice growers on the Gulf coast to secure seeds from the\r\nOrient suited to their conditions, and by giving them adequate\r\nprotection, they now supply home demand and export to the islands of the\r\nCaribbean Sea and to other rice-growing countries. Wheat and other\r\ngrains have been imported from light-rainfall countries to our lands in\r\nthe West and Southwest that have not grown crops because of light\r\nprecipitation, resulting in an extensive addition to our cropping area\r\nand our home-making territory that can not be irrigated. Ten million\r\nbushels of first-class macaroni wheat were grown from these experimental\r\nimportations last year. Fruits suitable to our soils and climates are\r\nbeing imported from all the countries of the Old World--the fig from\r\nTurkey, the almond from Spain, the date from Algeria, the mango from\r\nIndia. We are helping our fruit growers to get their crops into European\r\nmarkets by studying methods of preservation through refrigeration,\r\npacking, and handling, which have been quite successful. We are helping\r\nour hop growers by importing varieties that ripen earlier and later than\r\nthe kinds they have been raising, thereby lengthening the harvesting\r\nseason. The cotton crop of the country is threatened with root rot, the\r\nbollworm, and the boll weevil. Our pathologists will find immune\r\nvarieties that will resist the root disease, and the bollworm can be\r\ndealt with, but the boll weevil is a serious menace to the cotton crop.\r\nIt is a Central American insect that has become acclimated in Texas and\r\nhas done great damage. A scientist of the Department of Agriculture has\r\nfound the weevil at home in Guatemala being kept in check by an ant,\r\nwhich has been brought to our cotton fields for observation. It is hoped\r\nthat it may serve a good purpose.\r\n\r\nThe soils of the country are getting attention from the farmer's\r\nstandpoint, and interesting results are following. We have duplicates of\r\nthe soils that grow the wrapper tobacco in Sumatra and the filler\r\ntobacco in Cuba. It will be only a question of time when the large\r\namounts paid to these countries will be paid to our own people. The\r\nreclamation of alkali lands is progressing, to give object lessons to\r\nour people in methods by which worthless lands may be made productive.\r\n\r\nThe insect friends and enemies of the farmer are getting attention. The\r\nenemy of the San Jose scale was found near the Great Wall of China, and\r\nis now cleaning up all our orchards. The fig-fertilizing insect imported\r\nfrom Turkey has helped to establish an industry in California that\r\namounts to from fifty to one hundred tons of dried figs annually, and is\r\nextending over the Pacific coast. A parasitic fly from South Africa is\r\nkeeping in subjection the black scale, the worst pest of the orange and\r\nlemon industry in California.\r\n\r\nCareful preliminary work is being done towards producing our own silk.\r\nThe mulberry is being distributed in large numbers, eggs are being\r\nimported and distributed, improved reels were imported from Europe last\r\nyear, and two expert reelers were brought to Washington to reel the crop\r\nof cocoons and teach the art to our own people.\r\n\r\nThe crop-reporting system of the Department of Agriculture is being\r\nbrought closer to accuracy every year. It has two hundred and fifty\r\nthousand reporters selected from people in eight vocations in life. It\r\nhas arrangements with most European countries for interchange of\r\nestimates, so that our people may know as nearly as possible with what\r\nthey must compete.\r\n\r\nDuring the two and a half years that have elapsed since the passage of\r\nthe reclamation act rapid progress has been made in the surveys and\r\nexaminations of the opportunities for reclamation in the thirteen States\r\nand three Territories of the arid West. Construction has already been\r\nbegun on the largest and most important of the irrigation works, and\r\nplans are being completed for works which will utilize the funds now\r\navailable. The operations are being carried on by the Reclamation\r\nService, a corps of engineers selected through competitive civil-service\r\nexaminations. This corps includes experienced consulting and\r\nconstructing engineers as well as various experts in mechanical and\r\nlegal matters, and is composed largely of men who have spent most of\r\ntheir lives in practical affairs connected with irrigation. The larger\r\nproblems have been solved and it now remains to execute with care,\r\neconomy, and thoroughness the work which has been laid out. All\r\nimportant details are being carefully considered by boards of consulting\r\nengineers, selected for their thorough knowledge and practical\r\nexperience. Each project is taken up on the ground by competent men and\r\nviewed from the standpoint of the creation of prosperous homes, and of\r\npromptly refunding to the Treasury the cost of construction. The\r\nreclamation act has been found to be remarkably complete and effective,\r\nand so broad in its provisions that a wide range of undertakings has\r\nbeen possible under it. At the same time, economy is guaranteed by the\r\nfact that the funds must ultimately be returned to be used over again.\r\n\r\nIt is the cardinal principle of the forest-reserve policy of this\r\nAdministration that the reserves are for use. Whatever interferes with\r\nthe use of their resources is to be avoided by every possible means. But\r\nthese resources must be used in such a way as to make them permanent.\r\n\r\nThe forest policy of the Government is just now a subject of vivid\r\npublic interest throughout the West and to the people of the United\r\nStates in general. The forest reserves themselves are of extreme value\r\nto the present as well as to the future welfare of all the western\r\npublic-land States. They powerfully affect the use and disposal of the\r\npublic lands. They are of special importance because they preserve the\r\nwater supply and the supply of timber for domestic purposes, and so\r\npromote settlement under the reclamation act. Indeed, they are essential\r\nto the welfare of every one of the great interests of the West.\r\n\r\nForest reserves are created for two principal purposes. The first is to\r\npreserve the water supply. This is their most important use. The\r\nprincipal users of the water thus preserved are irrigation ranchers and\r\nsettlers, cities and towns to whom their municipal water supplies are of\r\nthe very first importance, users and furnishers of water power, and the\r\nusers of water for domestic, manufacturing, mining, and other purposes.\r\nAll these are directly dependent upon the forest reserves.\r\n\r\nThe second reason for which forest reserves are created is to preserve\r\nthe timber supply for various classes of wood users. Among the more\r\nimportant of these are settlers under the reclamation act and other\r\nacts, for whom a cheap and accessible supply of timber for domestic uses\r\nis absolutely necessary; miners and prospectors, who are in serious\r\ndanger of losing their timber supply by fire or through export by lumber\r\ncompanies when timber lands adjacent to their mines pass into private\r\nownership; lumbermen, transportation companies, builders, and commercial\r\ninterests in general.\r\n\r\nAlthough the wisdom of creating forest reserves is nearly everywhere\r\nheartily recognized, yet in a few localities there has been\r\nmisunderstanding and complaint. The following statement is therefore\r\ndesirable:\r\n\r\nThe forest reserve policy can be successful only when it has the full\r\nsupport of the people of the West. It can not safely, and should not in\r\nany case, be imposed upon them against their will. But neither can we\r\naccept the views of those whose only interest in the forest is\r\ntemporary; who are anxious to reap what they have not sown and then move\r\naway, leaving desolation behind them. On the contrary, it is everywhere\r\nand always the interest of the permanent settler and the permanent\r\nbusiness man, the man with a stake in the country, which must be\r\nconsidered and which must decide.\r\n\r\nThe making of forest reserves within railroad and wagon-road land-grant\r\nlimits will hereafter, as for the past three years, be so managed as to\r\nprevent the issue, under the act of June 4, 1897, of base for exchange\r\nor lieu selection (usually called scrip). In all cases where forest\r\nreserves within areas covered by land grants appear to be essential to\r\nthe prosperity of settlers, miners, or others, the Government lands\r\nwithin such proposed forest reserves will, as in the recent past, be\r\nwithdrawn from sale or entry pending the completion of such negotiations\r\nwith the owners of the land grants as will prevent the creation of\r\nso-called scrip.\r\n\r\nIt was formerly the custom to make forest reserves without first getting\r\ndefinite and detailed information as to the character of land and timber\r\nwithin their boundaries. This method of action often resulted in badly\r\nchosen boundaries and consequent injustice to settlers and others.\r\nTherefore this Administration adopted the present method of first\r\nwithdrawing the land from disposal, followed by careful examination on\r\nthe ground and the preparation of detailed maps and descriptions, before\r\nany forest reserve is created.\r\n\r\nI have repeatedly called attention to the confusion which exists in\r\nGovernment forest matters because the work is scattered among three\r\nindependent organizations. The United States is the only one of the\r\ngreat nations in which the forest work of the Government is not\r\nconcentrated under one department, in consonance with the plainest\r\ndictates of good administration and common sense. The present\r\narrangement is bad from every point of view. Merely to mention it is to\r\nprove that it should be terminated at once. As I have repeatedly\r\nrecommended, all the forest work of the Government should be\r\nconcentrated in the Department of Agriculture, where the larger part of\r\nthat work is already done, where practically all of the trained\r\nforesters of the Government are employed, where chiefly in Washington\r\nthere is comprehensive first-class knowledge of the problems of the\r\nreserves acquired on the ground, where all problems relating to growth\r\nfrom the soil are already gathered, and where all the sciences auxiliary\r\nto forestry are at hand for prompt and effective co-operation. These\r\nreasons are decisive in themselves, but it should be added that the\r\ngreat organizations of citizens whose interests are affected by the\r\nforest-reserves, such as the National Live Stock Association, the\r\nNational Wool Growers' Association, the American Mining Congress, the\r\nnational Irrigation Congress, and the National Board of Trade, have\r\nuniformly, emphatically, and most of them repeatedly, expressed\r\nthemselves in favor of placing all Government forest work in the\r\nDepartment of Agriculture because of the peculiar adaptation of that\r\nDepartment for it. It is true, also, that the forest services of nearly\r\nall the great nations of the world are under the respective departments\r\nof agriculture, while in but two of the smaller nations and in one\r\ncolony are they under the department of the interior. This is the result\r\nof long and varied experience and it agrees fully with the requirements\r\nof good administration in our own case.\r\n\r\nThe creation of a forest service in the Department of Agriculture will\r\nhave for its important results:\r\n\r\nFirst. A better handling of all forest work; because it will be under a\r\nsingle head, and because the vast and indispensable experience of the\r\nDepartment in all matters pertaining to the forest reserves, to forestry\r\nin general, and to other forms of production from the soil, will be\r\neasily and rapidly accessible.\r\n\r\nSecond. The reserves themselves, being handled from the point of view of\r\nthe man in the field, instead of the man in the office, will be more\r\neasily and more widely useful to the people of the West than has been\r\nthe case hitherto.\r\n\r\nThird. Within a comparatively short time the reserves will become\r\nself-supporting. This is important, because continually and rapidly\r\nincreasing appropriations will be necessary for the proper care of this\r\nexceedingly important interest of the Nation, and they can and should he\r\noffset by returns from the National forests. Under similar circumstances\r\nthe forest possessions of other great nations form an important source\r\nof revenue to their governments.\r\n\r\nEvery administrative officer concerned is convinced of the necessity for\r\nthe proposed consolidation of forest work in the Department of\r\nAgriculture, and I myself have urged it more than once in former\r\nmessages. Again I commend it to the early and favorable consideration of\r\nthe Congress. The interests of the Nation at large and of the West in\r\nparticular have suffered greatly because of the delay.\r\n\r\nI call the attention of the Congress again to the report and\r\nrecommendation of the Commission on the Public Lands forwarded by me to\r\nthe second session of the present Congress. The Commission has\r\nprosecuted its investigations actively during the past season, and a\r\nsecond report is now in an advanced stage of preparation.\r\n\r\nIn connection with the work of the forest reserves I desire again to\r\nurge upon the Congress the importance of authorizing the President to\r\nset aside certain portions of these reserves or other public lands as\r\ngame refuges for the preservation of the bison, the wapiti, and other\r\nlarge beasts once so abundant in our woods and mountains and on our\r\ngreat plains, and now tending toward extinction. Every support should be\r\ngiven to the authorities of the Yellowstone Park in their successful\r\nefforts at preserving the large creatures therein; and at very little\r\nexpense portions of the public domain in other regions which are wholly\r\nunsuited to agricultural settlement could be similarly utilized. We owe\r\nit to future generations to keep alive the noble and beautiful creatures\r\nwhich by their presence add such distinctive character to the American\r\nwilderness. The limits of the Yellowstone Park should be extended\r\nsouthwards. The Canyon of the Colorado should be made a national park;\r\nand the national-park system should include the Yosemite and as many as\r\npossible of the groves of giant trees in California.\r\n\r\nThe veterans of the Civil War have a claim upon the Nation such as no\r\nother body of our citizens possess. The Pension Bureau has never in its\r\nhistory been managed in a more satisfactory manner than is now the case.\r\n\r\nThe progress of the Indians toward civilization, though not rapid, is\r\nperhaps all that could be hoped for in view of the circumstances. Within\r\nthe past year many tribes have shown, in a degree greater than ever\r\nbefore, an appreciation of the necessity of work. This changed attitude\r\nis in part due to the policy recently pursued of reducing the amount of\r\nsubsistence to the Indians, and thus forcing them, through sheer\r\nnecessity, to work for a livelihood. The policy, though severe, is a\r\nuseful one, but it is to be exercised only with judgment and with a full\r\nunderstanding of the conditions which exist in each community for which\r\nit is intended. On or near the Indian reservations there is usually very\r\nlittle demand for labor, and if the Indians are to earn their living and\r\nwhen work can not be furnished from outside (which is always\r\npreferable), then it must be furnished by the Government. Practical\r\ninstruction of this kind would in a few years result in the forming of\r\nhabits of regular industry, which would render the Indian a producer and\r\nwould effect a great reduction in the cost of his maintenance.\r\n\r\nIt is commonly declared that the slow advance of the Indians is due to\r\nthe unsatisfactory character of the men appointed to take immediate\r\ncharge of them, and to some extent this is true. While the standard of\r\nthe employees in the Indian Service shows great improvement over that of\r\nbygone years, and while actual corruption or flagrant dishonesty is now\r\nthe rare exception, it is nevertheless the fact that the salaries paid\r\nIndian agents are not large enough to attract the best men to that field\r\nof work. To achieve satisfactory results the official in charge of an\r\nIndian tribe should possess the high qualifications which are required\r\nin the manager of a large business, but only in exceptional cases is it\r\npossible to secure men of such a type for these positions. Much better\r\nservice, however, might be obtained from those now holding the places\r\nwere it practicable to get out of them the best that is in them, and\r\nthis should be done by bringing them constantly into closer touch with\r\ntheir superior officers. An agent who has been content to draw his\r\nsalary, giving in return the least possible equivalent in effort and\r\nservice, may, by proper treatment, by suggestion and encouragement, or\r\npersistent urging, be stimulated to greater effort and induced to take a\r\nmore active personal interest in his work.\r\n\r\nUnder existing conditions an Indian agent in the distant West may be\r\nwholly out of touch with the office of the Indian Bureau. He may very\r\nwell feel that no one takes a personal interest in him or his efforts.\r\nCertain routine duties in the way of reports and accounts are required\r\nof him, but there is no one with whom he may intelligently consult on\r\nmatters vital to his work, except after long delay. Such a man would be\r\ngreatly encouraged and aided by personal contact with some one whose\r\ninterest in Indian affairs and whose authority in the Indian Bureau were\r\ngreater than his own, and such contact would be certain to arouse and\r\nconstantly increase the interest he takes in his work.\r\n\r\nThe distance which separates the agents--the workers in the field--from\r\nthe Indian Office in Washington is a chief obstacle to Indian progress.\r\nWhatever shall more closely unite these two branches of the Indian\r\nService, and shall enable them to co-operate more heartily and more\r\neffectively, will be for the increased efficiency of the work and the\r\nbetterment of the race for whose improvement the Indian Bureau was\r\nestablished. The appointment of a field assistant to the Commissioner of\r\nIndian Affairs would be certain to insure this good end. Such an\r\nofficial, if possessed of the requisite energy and deep interest in the\r\nwork, would be a most efficient factor in bringing into closer\r\nrelationship and a more direct union of effort the Bureau in Washington\r\nand its agents in the field; and with the co-operation of its branches\r\nthus secured the Indian Bureau would, in measure fuller than ever\r\nbefore, lift up the savage toward that self-help and self-reliance which\r\nconstitute the man.\r\n\r\nIn 1907 there will be held at Hampton Roads the tricentennial\r\ncelebration of the settlement at Jamestown, Virginia, with which the\r\nhistory of what has now become the United States really begins. I\r\ncommend this to your favorable consideration. It is an event of prime\r\nhistoric significance, in which all the people of the United States\r\nshould feel, and should show, great and general interest.\r\n\r\nIn the Post-Office Department the service has increased in efficiency,\r\nand conditions as to revenue and expenditure continue satisfactory. The\r\nincrease of revenue during the year was $9,358,181.10, or 6.9 per cent,\r\nthe total receipts amounting to $143,382,624.34. The expenditures were\r\n$152,362,116.70, an increase of about 9 per cent over the previous year,\r\nbeing thus $8,979,492.36 in excess of the current revenue. Included in\r\nthese expenditures was a total appropriation of $152,956,637.35 for the\r\ncontinuation and extension of the rural free-delivery service, which was\r\nan increase of $4,902,237.35 over the amount expended for this purpose\r\nin the preceding fiscal year. Large as this expenditure has been the\r\nbeneficent results attained in extending the free distribution of mails\r\nto the residents of rural districts have justified the wisdom of the\r\noutlay. Statistics brought down to the 1st of October, 1904, show that\r\non that date there were 27,138 rural routes established, serving\r\napproximately 12,000,000 of people in rural districts remote from\r\npost-offices, and that there were pending at that time 3,859 petitions\r\nfor the establishment of new rural routes. Unquestionably some part of\r\nthe general increase in receipts is due to the increased postal\r\nfacilities which the rural service has afforded. The revenues have also\r\nbeen aided greatly by amendments in the classification of mail matter,\r\nand the curtailment of abuses of the second-class mailing privilege. The\r\naverage increase in the volume of mail matter for the period beginning\r\nwith 1902 and ending June, 1905 (that portion for 1905 being estimated),\r\nis 40.47 per cent, as compared with 25.46 per cent for the period\r\nimmediately preceding, and 15.92 for the four-year period immediately\r\npreceding that.\r\n\r\nOur consular system needs improvement. Salaries should be substituted\r\nfor fees, and the proper classification, grading, and transfer of\r\nconsular officers should be provided. I am not prepared to say that a\r\ncompetitive system of examinations for appointment would work well; but\r\nby law it should be provided that consuls should be familiar, according\r\nto places for which they apply, with the French, German, or Spanish\r\nlanguages, and should possess acquaintance with the resources of the\r\nUnited States.\r\n\r\nThe collection of objects of art contemplated in section 5586 of the\r\nRevised Statutes should be designated and established as a National\r\nGallery of Art; and the Smithsonian Institution should be authorized to\r\naccept any additions to said collection that may be received by gift,\r\nbequest, or devise.\r\n\r\nIt is desirable to enact a proper National quarantine law. It is most\r\nundesirable that a State should on its own initiative enforce quarantine\r\nregulations which are in effect a restriction upon interstate and\r\ninternational commerce. The question should properly be assumed by the\r\nGovernment alone. The Surgeon-General of the National Public Health and\r\nMarine-Hospital Service has repeatedly and convincingly set forth the\r\nneed for such legislation.\r\n\r\nI call your attention to the great extravagance in printing and binding\r\nGovernment publications, and especially to the fact that altogether too\r\nmany of these publications are printed. There is a constant tendency to\r\nincrease their number and their volume. It is an understatement to say\r\nthat no appreciable harm would be caused by, and substantial benefit\r\nwould accrue from, decreasing the amount of printing now done by at\r\nleast one-half. Probably the great majority of the Government reports\r\nand the like now printed are never read at all, and furthermore the\r\nprinting of much of the material contained in many of the remaining ones\r\nserves no useful purpose whatever.\r\n\r\nThe attention of the Congress should be especially given to the currency\r\nquestion, and that the standing committees on the matter in the two\r\nHouses charged with the duty, take up the matter of our currency and see\r\nwhether it is not possible to secure an agreement in the business world\r\nfor bettering the system; the committees should consider the question of\r\nthe retirement of the greenbacks and the problem of securing in our\r\ncurrency such elasticity as is consistent with safety. Every silver\r\ndollar should be made by law redeemable in gold at the option of the\r\nholder.\r\n\r\nI especially commend to your immediate attention the encouragement of\r\nour merchant marine by appropriate legislation.\r\n\r\nThe growing importance of the Orient as a field for American exports\r\ndrew from my predecessor, President McKinley, an urgent request for its\r\nspecial consideration by the Congress. In his message of 1898 he stated:\r\n\r\n\"In this relation, as showing the peculiar volume and value of our trade\r\nwith China and the peculiarly favorable conditions which exist for their\r\nexpansion in the normal course of trade, I refer to the communication\r\naddressed to the Speaker of the House of Representatives by the\r\nSecretary of the Treasury on the 14th of last June, with its\r\naccompanying letter of the Secretary of State, recommending an\r\nappropriation for a commission to study the industrial and commercial\r\nconditions in the Chinese Empire and to report as to the opportunities\r\nfor and the obstacles to the enlargement of markets in China for the raw\r\nproducts and manufactures of the United States. Action was not taken\r\nthereon during the last session. I cordially urge that the\r\nrecommendation receive at your hands the consideration which its\r\nimportance and timeliness merit.\"\r\n\r\nIn his annual message of 1889 he again called attention to this\r\nrecommendation, quoting it, and stated further:\r\n\r\n\"I now renew this recommendation, as the importance of the subject has\r\nsteadily grown since it was first submitted to you, and no time should\r\nbe lost in studying for ourselves the resources of this great field for\r\nAmerican trade and enterprise.\"\r\n\r\nThe importance of securing proper information and data with a view to\r\nthe enlargement of our trade with Asia is undiminished. Our consular\r\nrepresentatives in China have strongly urged a place for permanent\r\ndisplay of American products in some prominent trade center of that\r\nEmpire, under Government control and management, as an effective means\r\nof advancing our export trade therein. I call the attention of the\r\nCongress to the desirability of carrying out these suggestions.\r\n\r\nIn dealing with the questions of immigration and naturalization it is\r\nindispensable to keep certain facts ever before the minds of those who\r\nshare in enacting the laws. First and foremost, let us remember that the\r\nquestion of being a good American has nothing whatever to do with a\r\nman's birthplace any more than it has to do with his creed. In every\r\ngeneration from the time this Government was founded men of foreign\r\nbirth have stood in the very foremost rank of good citizenship, and that\r\nnot merely in one but in every field of American activity; while to try\r\nto draw a distinction between the man whose parents came to this country\r\nand the man whose ancestors came to it several generations back is a\r\nmere absurdity. Good Americanism is a matter of heart, of conscience, of\r\nlofty aspiration, of sound common sense, but not of birthplace or of\r\ncreed. The medal of honor, the highest prize to be won by those who\r\nserve in the Army and the Navy of the United States decorates men born\r\nhere, and it also decorates men born in Great Britain and Ireland, in\r\nGermany, in Scandinavia, in France, and doubtless in other countries\r\nalso. In the field of statesmanship, in the field of business, in the\r\nfield of philanthropic endeavor, it is equally true that among the men\r\nof whom we are most proud as Americans no distinction whatever can be\r\ndrawn between those who themselves or whose parents came over in sailing\r\nship or steamer from across the water and those whose ancestors stepped\r\nashore into the wooded wilderness at Plymouth or at the mouth of the\r\nHudson, the Delaware, or the James nearly three centuries ago. No\r\nfellow-citizen of ours is entitled to any peculiar regard because of the\r\nway in which he worships his Maker, or because of the birthplace of\r\nhimself or his parents, nor should he be in any way discriminated\r\nagainst therefor. Each must stand on his worth as a man and each is\r\nentitled to be judged solely thereby.\r\n\r\nThere is no danger of having too many immigrants of the right kind. It\r\nmakes no difference from what country they come. If they are sound in\r\nbody and in mind, and, above all, if they are of good character, so that\r\nwe can rest assured that their children and grandchildren will be worthy\r\nfellow-citizens of our children and grandchildren, then we should\r\nwelcome them with cordial hospitality.\r\n\r\nBut the citizenship of this country should not be debased. It is vital\r\nthat we should keep high the standard of well-being among our\r\nwage-workers, and therefore we should not admit masses of men whose\r\nstandards of living and whose personal customs and habits are such that\r\nthey tend to lower the level of the American wage-worker; and above all\r\nwe should not admit any man of an unworthy type, any man concerning whom\r\nwe can say that he will himself be a bad citizen, or that his children\r\nand grandchildren will detract from instead of adding to the sum of the\r\ngood citizenship of the country. Similarly we should take the greatest\r\ncare about naturalization. Fraudulent naturalization, the naturalization\r\nof improper persons, is a curse to our Government; and it is the affair\r\nof every honest voter, wherever born, to see that no fraudulent voting\r\nis allowed, that no fraud in connection with naturalization is\r\npermitted.\r\n\r\nIn the past year the cases of false, fraudulent, and improper\r\nnaturalization of aliens coming to the attention of the executive\r\nbranches of the Government have increased to an alarming degree.\r\nExtensive sales of forged certificates of naturalization have been\r\ndiscovered, as well as many cases of naturalization secured by perjury\r\nand fraud; and in addition, instances have accumulated showing that many\r\ncourts issue certificates of naturalization carelessly and upon\r\ninsufficient evidence.\r\n\r\nUnder the Constitution it is in the power of the Congress \"to establish\r\na uniform rule of naturalization,\" and numerous laws have from time to\r\ntime been enacted for that purpose, which have been supplemented in a\r\nfew States by State laws having special application. The Federal\r\nstatutes permit naturalization by any court of record in the United\r\nStates having common-law jurisdiction and a seal and clerk, except the\r\npolice court of the District of Columbia, and nearly all these courts\r\nexercise this important function. It results that where so many courts\r\nof such varying grades have jurisdiction, there is lack of uniformity in\r\nthe rules applied in conferring naturalization. Some courts are strict\r\nand others lax. An alien who may secure naturalization in one place\r\nmight be denied it in another, and the intent of the constitutional\r\nprovision is in fact defeated. Furthermore, the certificates of\r\nnaturalization issued by the courts differ widely in wording and\r\nappearance, and when they are brought into use in foreign countries, are\r\nfrequently subject to suspicion.\r\n\r\nThere should be a comprehensive revision of the naturalization laws. The\r\ncourts having power to naturalize should be definitely named by national\r\nauthority; the testimony upon which naturalization may be conferred\r\nshould be definitely prescribed; publication of impending naturalization\r\napplications should be required in advance of their hearing in court;\r\nthe form and wording of all certificates issued should be uniform\r\nthroughout the country, and the courts should be required to make\r\nreturns to the Secretary of State at stated periods of all\r\nnaturalizations conferred.\r\n\r\nNot only are the laws relating to naturalization now defective, but\r\nthose relating to citizenship of the United States ought also to be made\r\nthe subject of scientific inquiry with a view to probable further\r\nlegislation. By what acts expatriation may be assumed to have been\r\naccomplished, how long an American citizen may reside abroad and receive\r\nthe protection of our passport, whether any degree of protection should\r\nbe extended to one who has made the declaration of intention to become a\r\ncitizen of the United States but has not secured naturalization, are\r\nquestions of serious import, involving personal rights and often\r\nproducing friction between this Government and foreign governments. Yet\r\nupon these question our laws are silent. I recommend that an examination\r\nbe made into the subjects of citizenship, expatriation, and protection\r\nof Americans abroad, with a view to appropriate legislation.\r\n\r\nThe power of the Government to protect the integrity of the elections of\r\nits own officials is inherent and has been recognized and affirmed by\r\nrepeated declarations of the Supreme Court. There is no enemy of free\r\ngovernment more dangerous and none so insidious as the corruption of the\r\nelectorate. No one defends or excuses corruption, and it would seem to\r\nfollow that none would oppose vigorous measures to eradicate it. I\r\nrecommend the enactment of a law directed against bribery and corruption\r\nin Federal elections. The details of such a law may be safely left to\r\nthe wise discretion of the Congress, but it should go as far as under\r\nthe Constitution it is possible to go, and should include severe\r\npenalties against him who gives or receives a bribe intended to\r\ninfluence his act or opinion as an elector; and provisions for the\r\npublication not only of the expenditures for nominations and elections\r\nof all candidates but also of all contributions received and\r\nexpenditures made by political committees.\r\n\r\nNo subject is better worthy the attention of the Congress than that\r\nportion of the report of the Attorney-General dealing with the long\r\ndelays and the great obstruction to justice experienced in the cases of\r\nBeavers, Green and Gaynor, and Benson. Were these isolated and special\r\ncases, I should not call your attention to them; but the difficulties\r\nencountered as regards these men who have been indicted for criminal\r\npractices are not exceptional; they are precisely similar in kind to\r\nwhat occurs again and again in the case of criminals who have sufficient\r\nmeans to enable them to take advantage of a system of procedure which\r\nhas grown up in the Federal courts and which amounts in effect to making\r\nthe law easy of enforcement against the man who has no money, and\r\ndifficult of enforcement, even to the point of sometimes securing\r\nimmunity, as regards the man who has money. In criminal cases the writ\r\nof the United States should run throughout its borders. The wheels of\r\njustice should not be clogged, as they have been clogged in the cases\r\nabove mentioned, where it has proved absolutely impossible to bring the\r\naccused to the place appointed by the Constitution for his trial. Of\r\nrecent years there has been grave and increasing complaint of the\r\ndifficulty of bringing to justice those criminals whose criminality,\r\ninstead of being against one person in the Republic, is against all\r\npersons in the Republic, because it is against the Republic itself.\r\nUnder any circumstance and from the very nature of the case it is often\r\nexceedingly difficult to secure proper punishment of those who have been\r\nguilty of wrongdoing against the Government. By the time the offender\r\ncan be brought into court the popular wrath against him has generally\r\nsubsided; and there is in most instances very slight danger indeed of\r\nany prejudice existing in the minds of the jury against him. At present\r\nthe interests of the innocent man are amply safeguarded; but the\r\ninterests of the Government, that is, the interests of honest\r\nadministration, that is the interests of the people, are not recognized\r\nas they should be. No subject better warrants the attention of the\r\nCongress. Indeed, no subject better warrants the attention of the bench\r\nand the bar throughout the United States.\r\n\r\nAlaska, like all our Territorial acquisitions, has proved resourceful\r\nbeyond the expectations of those who made the purchase. It has become\r\nthe home of many hardy, industrious, and thrifty American citizens.\r\nTowns of a permanent character have been built. The extent of its wealth\r\nin minerals, timber, fisheries, and agriculture, while great, is\r\nprobably not comprehended yet in any just measure by our people. We do\r\nknow, however, that from a very small beginning its products have grown\r\nuntil they are a steady and material contribution to the wealth of the\r\nnation. Owing to the immensity of Alaska and its location in the far\r\nnorth, it is a difficult matter to provide many things essential to its\r\ngrowth and to the happiness and comfort of its people by private\r\nenterprise alone. It should, therefore, receive reasonable aid from the\r\nGovernment. The Government has already done excellent work for Alaska in\r\nlaying cables and building telegraph lines. This work has been done in\r\nthe most economical and efficient way by the Signal Corps of the Army.\r\n\r\nIn some respects it has outgrown its present laws, while in others those\r\nlaws have been found to be inadequate. In order to obtain information\r\nupon which I could rely I caused an official of the Department of\r\nJustice, in whose judgment I have confidence, to visit Alaska during the\r\npast summer for the purpose of ascertaining how government is\r\nadministered there and what legislation is actually needed at present. A\r\nstatement of the conditions found to exist, together with some\r\nrecommendations and the reasons therefor, in which I strongly concur,\r\nwill be found in the annual report of the Attorney-General. In some\r\ninstances I feel that the legislation suggested is so imperatively\r\nneeded that I am moved briefly to emphasize the Attorney-General's\r\nproposals.\r\n\r\nUnder the Code of Alaska as it now stands many purely administrative\r\npowers and duties, including by far the most important, devolve upon the\r\ndistrict judges or upon the clerks of the district court acting under\r\nthe direction of the judges, while the governor, upon whom these powers\r\nand duties should logically fall, has nothing specific to do except to\r\nmake annual reports, issue Thanksgiving Day proclamations, and appoint\r\nIndian policemen and notaries public. I believe it essential to good\r\ngovernment in Alaska, and therefore recommend, that the Congress divest\r\nthe district judges and the clerks of their courts of the administrative\r\nor executive functions that they now exercise and cast them upon the\r\ngovernor. This would not be an innovation; it would simply conform the\r\ngovernment of Alaska to fundamental principles, making the governorship\r\na real instead of a merely nominal office, and leaving the judges free\r\nto give their entire attention to their judicial duties and at the same\r\ntime removing them from a great deal of the strife that now embarrasses\r\nthe judicial office in Alaska.\r\n\r\nI also recommend that the salaries of the district judges and district\r\nattorneys in Alaska be increased so as to make them equal to those\r\nreceived by corresponding officers in the United States after deducting\r\nthe difference in the cost of living; that the district attorneys should\r\nbe prohibited from engaging in private practice; that United States\r\ncommissioners be appointed by the governor of the Territory instead of\r\nby the district judges, and that a fixed salary be provided for them to\r\ntake the place of the discredited \"fee system,\" which should be\r\nabolished in all offices; that a mounted constabulary be created to\r\npolice the territory outside the limits of incorporated towns--a vast\r\nsection now wholly without police protection; and that some provision be\r\nmade to at least lessen the oppressive delays and costs that now attend\r\nthe prosecution of appeals from the district court of Alaska. There\r\nshould be a division of the existing judicial districts, and an increase\r\nin the number of judges.\r\n\r\nAlaska should have a Delegate in the Congress. Where possible, the\r\nCongress should aid in the construction of needed wagon roads.\r\nAdditional light-houses should be provided. In my judgment, it is\r\nespecially important to aid in such manner as seems just and feasible in\r\nthe construction of a trunk line of railway to connect the Gulf of\r\nAlaska with the Yukon River through American territory. This would be\r\nmost beneficial to the development of the resources of the Territory,\r\nand to the comfort and welfare of its people.\r\n\r\nSalmon hatcheries should be established in many different streams, so as\r\nto secure the preservation of this valuable food fish. Salmon fisheries\r\nand canneries should be prohibited on certain of the rivers where the\r\nmass of those Indians dwell who live almost exclusively on fish.\r\n\r\nThe Alaskan natives are kindly, intelligent, anxious to learn, and\r\nwilling to work. Those who have come under the influence of\r\ncivilization, even for a limited period, have proved their capability of\r\nbecoming self-supporting, self-respecting citizens, and ask only for the\r\njust enforcement of law and intelligent instruction and supervision.\r\nOthers, living in more remote regions, primitive, simple hunters and\r\nfisher folk, who know only the life of the woods and the waters, are\r\ndaily being confronted with twentieth-century civilization with all of\r\nits complexities. Their country is being overrun by strangers, the game\r\nslaughtered and driven away, the streams depleted of fish, and hitherto\r\nunknown and fatal diseases brought to them, all of which combine to\r\nproduce a state of abject poverty and want which must result in their\r\nextinction.
