Action in their interest is demanded by every consideration\r\nof justice and humanity.\r\n\r\nThe needs of these people are:\r\n\r\nThe abolition of the present fee system, whereby the native is degraded,\r\nimposed upon, and taught the injustice of law.\r\n\r\nThe establishment of hospitals at central points, so that contagious\r\ndiseases that are brought to them continually by incoming whites may be\r\nlocalized and not allowed to become epidemic, to spread death and\r\ndestitution over great areas.\r\n\r\nThe development of the educational system in the form of practical\r\ntraining in such industries as will assure the Indians self-support\r\nunder the changed conditions in which they will have to live.\r\n\r\nThe duties of the office of the governor should be extended to include\r\nthe supervision of Indian affairs, with necessary assistants in\r\ndifferent districts. He should be provided with the means and the power\r\nto protect and advise the native people, to furnish medical treatment in\r\ntime of epidemics, and to extend material relief in periods of famine\r\nand extreme destitution.\r\n\r\nThe Alaskan natives should be given the right to acquire, hold, and\r\ndispose of property upon the same conditions as given other inhabitants;\r\nand the privilege of citizenship should be given to such as may be able\r\nto meet certain definite requirements. In Hawaii Congress should give\r\nthe governor power to remove all the officials appointed under him. The\r\nharbor of Honolulu should be dredged. The Marine-Hospital Service should\r\nbe empowered to study leprosy in the islands. I ask special\r\nconsideration for the report and recommendation of the governor of Porto\r\nRico.\r\n\r\nIn treating of our foreign policy and of the attitude that this great\r\nNation should assume in the world at large, it is absolutely necessary\r\nto consider the Army and the Navy, and the Congress, through which the\r\nthought of the Nation finds its expression, should keep ever vividly in\r\nmind the fundamental fact that it is impossible to treat our foreign\r\npolicy, whether this policy takes shape in the effort to secure justice\r\nfor others or justice for ourselves, save as conditioned upon the\r\nattitude we are willing to take toward our Army, and especially toward\r\nour Navy. It is not merely unwise, it is contemptible, for a nation, as\r\nfor an individual, to use high-sounding language to proclaim its\r\npurposes, or to take positions which are ridiculous if unsupported by\r\npotential force, and then to refuse to provide this force. If there is\r\nno intention of providing and of keeping the force necessary to back up\r\na strong attitude, then it is far better not to assume such an attitude.\r\n\r\nThe steady aim of this Nation, as of all enlightened nations, should be\r\nto strive to bring ever nearer the day when there shall prevail\r\nthroughout the world the peace of justice. There are kinds of peace\r\nwhich are highly undesirable, which are in the long run as destructive\r\nas any war. Tyrants and oppressors have many times made a wilderness and\r\ncalled it peace. Many times peoples who were slothful or timid or\r\nshortsighted, who had been enervated by ease or by luxury, or misled by\r\nfalse teachings, have shrunk in unmanly fashion from doing duty that was\r\nstern and that needed self-sacrifice, and have sought to hide from their\r\nown minds their shortcomings, their ignoble motives, by calling them\r\nlove of peace. The peace of tyrannous terror, the peace of craven\r\nweakness, the peace of injustice, all these should be shunned as we shun\r\nunrighteous war. The goal to set before us as a nation, the goal which\r\nshould be set before all mankind, is the attainment of the peace of\r\njustice, of the peace which comes when each nation is not merely\r\nsafe-guarded in its own rights, but scrupulously recognizes and performs\r\nits duty toward others. Generally peace tells for righteousness; but if\r\nthere is conflict between the two, then our fealty is due-first to the\r\ncause of righteousness. Unrighteous wars are common, and unrighteous\r\npeace is rare; but both should be shunned. The right of freedom and the\r\nresponsibility for the exercise of that right can not be divorced. One\r\nof our great poets has well and finely said that freedom is not a gift\r\nthat tarries long in the hands of cowards. Neither does it tarry long in\r\nthe hands of those too slothful, too dishonest, or too unintelligent to\r\nexercise it. The eternal vigilance which is the price of liberty must be\r\nexercised, sometimes to guard against outside foes; although of course\r\nfar more often to guard against our own selfish or thoughtless\r\nshortcomings.\r\n\r\nIf these self-evident truths are kept before us, and only if they are so\r\nkept before us, we shall have a clear idea of what our foreign policy in\r\nits larger aspects should be. It is our duty to remember that a nation\r\nhas no more right to do injustice to another nation, strong or weak,\r\nthan an individual has to do injustice to another individual; that the\r\nsame moral law applies in one case as in the other. But we must also\r\nremember that it is as much the duty of the Nation to guard its own\r\nrights and its own interests as it is the duty of the individual so to\r\ndo. Within the Nation the individual has now delegated this right to the\r\nState, that is, to the representative of all the individuals, and it is\r\na maxim of the law that for every wrong there is a remedy. But in\r\ninternational law we have not advanced by any means as far as we have\r\nadvanced in municipal law. There is as yet no judicial way of enforcing\r\na right in international law. When one nation wrongs another or wrongs\r\nmany others, there is no tribunal before which the wrongdoer can be\r\nbrought. Either it is necessary supinely to acquiesce in the wrong, and\r\nthus put a premium upon brutality and aggression, or else it is\r\nnecessary for the aggrieved nation valiantly to stand up for its rights.\r\nUntil some method is devised by which there shall be a degree of\r\ninternational control over offending nations, it would be a wicked thing\r\nfor the most civilized powers, for those with most sense of\r\ninternational obligations and with keenest and most generous\r\nappreciation of the difference between right and wrong, to disarm. If\r\nthe great civilized nations of the present day should completely disarm,\r\nthe result would mean an immediate recrudescence of barbarism in one\r\nform or another. Under any circumstances a sufficient armament would\r\nhave to be kept up to serve the purposes of international police; and\r\nuntil international cohesion and the sense of international duties and\r\nrights are far more advanced than at present, a nation desirous both of\r\nsecuring respect for itself and of doing good to others must have a\r\nforce adequate for the work which it feels is allotted to it as its part\r\nof the general world duty. Therefore it follows that a self-respecting,\r\njust, and far-seeing nation should on the one hand endeavor by every\r\nmeans to aid in the development of the various movements which tend to\r\nprovide substitutes for war, which tend to render nations in their\r\nactions toward one another, and indeed toward their own peoples, more\r\nresponsive to the general sentiment of humane and civilized mankind; and\r\non the other hand that it should keep prepared, while scrupulously\r\navoiding wrongdoing itself, to repel any wrong, and in exceptional cases\r\nto take action which in a more advanced stage of international relations\r\nwould come under the head of the exercise of the international police. A\r\ngreat free people owes it to itself and to all mankind not to sink into\r\nhelplessness before the powers of evil.\r\n\r\nWe are in every way endeavoring to help on, with cordial good will,\r\nevery movement which will tend to bring us into more friendly relations\r\nwith the rest of mankind. In pursuance of this policy I shall shortly\r\nlay before the Senate treaties of arbitration with all powers which are\r\nwilling to enter into these treaties with us. It is not possible at this\r\nperiod of the world's development to agree to arbitrate all matters, but\r\nthere are many matters of possible difference between us and other\r\nnations which can be thus arbitrated. Furthermore, at the request of the\r\nInterparliamentary Union, an eminent body composed of practical\r\nstatesmen from all countries, I have asked the Powers to join with this\r\nGovernment in a second Hague conference, at which it is hoped that the\r\nwork already so happily begun at The Hague may be carried some steps\r\nfurther toward completion. This carries out the desire expressed by the\r\nfirst Hague conference itself.\r\n\r\nIt is not true that the United States feels any land hunger or\r\nentertains any projects as regards the other nations of the Western\r\nHemisphere save such as are for their welfare. All that this country\r\ndesires is to see the neighboring countries stable, orderly, and\r\nprosperous. Any country whose people conduct themselves well can count\r\nupon our hearty friendship. If a nation shows that it knows how to act\r\nwith reasonable efficiency and decency in social and political matters,\r\nif it keeps order and pays its obligations, it need fear no interference\r\nfrom the United States. Chronic wrongdoing, or an impotence which\r\nresults in a general loosening of the ties of civilized society, may in\r\nAmerica, as elsewhere, ultimately require intervention by some civilized\r\nnation, and in the Western Hemisphere the adherence of the United States\r\nto the Monroe Doctrine may force the United States, however reluctantly,\r\nin flagrant cases of such wrongdoing or impotence, to the exercise of an\r\ninternational police power. If every country washed by the Caribbean Sea\r\nwould show the progress in stable and just civilization which with the\r\naid of the Platt amendment Cuba has shown since our troops left the\r\nisland, and which so many of the republics in both Americas are\r\nconstantly and brilliantly showing, all question of interference by this\r\nNation with their affairs would be at an end. Our interests and those of\r\nour southern neighbors are in reality identical. They have great natural\r\nriches, and if within their borders the reign of law and justice\r\nobtains, prosperity is sure to come to them. While they thus obey the\r\nprimary laws of civilized society they may rest assured that they will\r\nbe treated by us in a spirit of cordial and helpful sympathy. We would\r\ninterfere with them only in the last resort, and then only if it became\r\nevident that their inability or unwillingness to do justice at home and\r\nabroad had violated the rights of the United States or had invited\r\nforeign aggression to the detriment of the entire body of American\r\nnations. It is a mere truism to say that every nation, whether in\r\nAmerica or anywhere else, which desires to maintain its freedom, its\r\nindependence, must ultimately realize that the right of such\r\nindependence can not be separated from the responsibility of making good\r\nuse of it.\r\n\r\nIn asserting the Monroe Doctrine, in taking such steps as we have taken\r\nin regard to Cuba, Venezuela, and Panama, and in endeavoring to\r\ncircumscribe the theater of war in the Far East, and to secure the open\r\ndoor in China, we have acted in our own interest as well as in the\r\ninterest of humanity at large. There are, however, cases in which, while\r\nour own interests are not greatly involved, strong appeal is made to our\r\nsympathies. Ordinarily it is very much wiser and more useful for us to\r\nconcern ourselves with striving for our own moral and material\r\nbetterment here at home than to concern ourselves with trying to better\r\nthe condition of things in other nations. We have plenty of sins of our\r\nown to war against, and under ordinary circumstances we can do more for\r\nthe general uplifting of humanity by striving with heart and soul to put\r\na stop to civic corruption, to brutal lawlessness and violent race\r\nprejudices here at home than by passing resolutions about wrongdoing\r\nelsewhere. Nevertheless there are occasional crimes committed on so vast\r\na scale and of such peculiar horror as to make us doubt whether it is\r\nnot our manifest duty to endeavor at least to show our disapproval of\r\nthe deed and our sympathy with those who have suffered by it. The cases\r\nmust be extreme in which such a course is justifiable. There must be no\r\neffort made to remove the mote from our brother's eye if we refuse to\r\nremove the beam from our own. But in extreme cases action may be\r\njustifiable and proper. What form the action shall take must depend upon\r\nthe circumstances of the case; that is, upon the degree of the atrocity\r\nand upon our power to remedy it. The cases in which we could interfere\r\nby force of arms as we interfered to put a stop to intolerable\r\nconditions in Cuba are necessarily very few. Yet it is not to be\r\nexpected that a people like ours, which in spite of certain very obvious\r\nshortcomings, nevertheless as a whole shows by its consistent practice\r\nits belief in the principles of civil and religious liberty and of\r\norderly freedom, a people among whom even the worst crime, like the\r\ncrime of lynching, is never more than sporadic, so that individuals and\r\nnot classes are molested in their fundamental rights--it is inevitable\r\nthat such a nation should desire eagerly to give expression to its\r\nhorror on an occasion like that of the massacre of the Jews in Kishenef,\r\nor when it witnesses such systematic and long-extended cruelty and\r\noppression as the cruelty and oppression of which the Armenians have\r\nbeen the victims, and which have won for them the indignant pity of the\r\ncivilized world.\r\n\r\nEven where it is not possible to secure in other nations the observance\r\nof the principles which we accept as axiomatic, it is necessary for us\r\nfirmly to insist upon the rights of our own citizens without regard to\r\ntheir creed or race; without regard to whether they were born here or\r\nborn abroad. It has proved very difficult to secure from Russia the\r\nright for our Jewish fellow-citizens to receive passports and travel\r\nthrough Russian territory. Such conduct is not only unjust and\r\nirritating toward us, but it is difficult to see its wisdom from\r\nRussia's standpoint. No conceivable good is accomplished by it. If an\r\nAmerican Jew or an American Christian misbehaves himself in Russia he\r\ncan at once be driven out; but the ordinary American Jew, like the\r\nordinary American Christian, would behave just about as he behaves here,\r\nthat is, behave as any good citizen ought to behave; and where this is\r\nthe case it is a wrong against which we are entitled to protest to\r\nrefuse him his passport without regard to his conduct and character,\r\nmerely on racial and religious grounds. In Turkey our difficulties arise\r\nless from the way in which our citizens are sometimes treated than from\r\nthe indignation inevitably excited in seeing such fearful misrule as has\r\nbeen witnessed both in Armenia and Macedonia.\r\n\r\nThe strong arm of the Government in enforcing respect for its just\r\nrights in international matters is the Navy of the United States. I most\r\nearnestly recommend that there be no halt in the work of upbuilding the\r\nAmerican Navy. There is no more patriotic duty before us a people than\r\nto keep the Navy adequate to the needs of this country's position. We\r\nhave undertaken to build the Isthmian Canal. We have undertaken to\r\nsecure for ourselves our just share in the trade of the Orient. We have\r\nundertaken to protect our citizens from proper treatment in foreign\r\nlands. We continue steadily to insist on the application of the Monroe\r\nDoctrine to the Western Hemisphere. Unless our attitude in these and all\r\nsimilar matters is to be a mere boastful sham we can not afford to\r\nabandon our naval programme. Our voice is now potent for peace, and is\r\nso potent because we are not afraid of war. But our protestations upon\r\nbehalf of peace would neither receive nor deserve the slightest\r\nattention if we were impotent to make them good.\r\n\r\nThe war which now unfortunately rages in the far East has emphasized in\r\nstriking fashion the new possibilities of naval warfare. The lessons\r\ntaught are both strategic and tactical, and are political as well as\r\nmilitary. The experiences of the war have shown in conclusive fashion\r\nthat while sea-going and sea-keeping torpedo destroyers are\r\nindispensable, and fast lightly armed and armored cruisers very useful,\r\nyet that the main reliance, the main standby, in any navy worthy the\r\nname must be the great battle ships, heavily armored and heavily gunned.\r\nNot a Russian or Japanese battle ship has been sunk by a torpedo boat,\r\nor by gunfire, while among the less protected ships, cruiser after\r\ncruiser has been destroyed whenever the hostile squadrons have gotten\r\nwithin range of one another's weapons. There will always be a large\r\nfield of usefulness for cruisers, especially of the more formidable\r\ntype. We need to increase the number of torpedo-boat destroyers, paying\r\nless heed to their having a knot or two extra speed than to their\r\ncapacity to keep the seas for weeks, and, if necessary, for months at a\r\ntime. It is wise to build submarine torpedo boats, as under certain\r\ncircumstances they might be very useful. But most of all we need to\r\ncontinue building our fleet of battle ships, or ships so powerfully\r\narmed that they can inflict the maximum of damage upon our opponents,\r\nand so well protected that they can suffer a severe hammering in return\r\nwithout fatal impairment of their ability to fight and maneuver. Of\r\ncourse ample means must be provided for enabling the personnel of the\r\nNavy to be brought to the highest point of efficiency. Our great\r\nfighting ships and torpedo boats must be ceaselessly trained and\r\nmaneuvered in squadrons. The officers and men can only learn their trade\r\nthoroughly by ceaseless practice on the high seas. In the event of war\r\nit would be far better to have no ships at all than to have ships of a\r\npoor and ineffective type, or ships which, however good, were yet manned\r\nby untrained and unskillful crews. The best officers and men in a poor\r\nship could do nothing against fairly good opponents; and on the other\r\nhand a modern war ship is useless unless the officers and men aboard her\r\nhave become adepts in their duties. The marksmanship in our Navy has\r\nimproved in an extraordinary degree during the last three years, and on\r\nthe whole the types of our battleships are improving; but much remains\r\nto be done. Sooner or later we shall have to provide for some method by\r\nwhich there will be promotions for merit as well as for seniority, or\r\nelse retirement all those who after a certain age have not advanced\r\nbeyond a certain grade; while no effort must be spared to make the\r\nservice attractive to the enlisted men in order that they may be kept as\r\nlong as possible in it. Reservation public schools should be provided\r\nwherever there are navy-yards.\r\n\r\nWithin the last three years the United States has set an example in\r\ndisarmament where disarmament was proper. By law our Army is fixed at a\r\nmaximum of one hundred thousand and a minimum of sixty thousand men.\r\nWhen there was insurrection in the Philippines we kept the Army at the\r\nmaximum. Peace came in the Philippines, and now our Army has been\r\nreduced to the minimum at which it is possible to keep it with due\r\nregard to its efficiency. The guns now mounted require twenty-eight\r\nthousand men, if the coast fortifications are to be adequately manned.\r\nRelatively to the Nation, it is not now so large as the police force of\r\nNew York or Chicago relatively to the population of either city. We need\r\nmore officers; there are not enough to perform the regular army work. It\r\nis very important that the officers of the Army should be accustomed to\r\nhandle their men in masses, as it is also important that the National\r\nGuard of the several States should be accustomed to actual field\r\nmaneuvering, especially in connection with the regulars. For this reason\r\nwe are to be congratulated upon the success of the field maneuvers at\r\nManassas last fall, maneuvers in which a larger number of Regulars and\r\nNational Guard took part than was ever before assembled together in time\r\nof peace. No other civilized nation has, relatively to its population,\r\nsuch a diminutive Army as ours; and while the Army is so small we are\r\nnot to be excused if we fail to keep it at a very high grade of\r\nproficiency. It must be incessantly practiced; the standard for the\r\nenlisted men should be kept very high, while at the same time the\r\nservice should be made as attractive as possible; and the standard for\r\nthe officers should be kept even higher--which, as regards the upper\r\nranks, can best be done by introducing some system of selection and\r\nrejection into the promotions. We should be able, in the event of some\r\nsudden emergency, to put into the field one first-class army corps,\r\nwhich should be, as a whole, at least the equal of any body of troops of\r\nlike number belonging to any other nation.\r\n\r\nGreat progress has been made in protecting our coasts by adequate\r\nfortifications with sufficient guns. We should, however, pay much more\r\nheed than at present to the development of an extensive system of\r\nfloating mines for use in all our more important harbors. These mines\r\nhave been proved to be a most formidable safeguard against hostile\r\nfleets.\r\n\r\nI earnestly call the attention of the Congress to the need of amending\r\nthe existing law relating to the award of Congressional medals of honor\r\nin the Navy so as to provide that they may be awarded to commissioned\r\nofficers and warrant officers as well as to enlisted men. These justly\r\nprized medals are given in the Army alike to the officers and the\r\nenlisted men, and it is most unjust that the commissioned officers and\r\nwarrant officers of the Navy should not in this respect have the same\r\nrights as their brethren in the Army and as the enlisted men of the\r\nNavy.\r\n\r\nIn the Philippine Islands there has been during the past year a\r\ncontinuation of the steady progress which has obtained ever since our\r\ntroops definitely got the upper hand of the insurgents. The Philippine\r\npeople, or, to speak more accurately, the many tribes, and even races,\r\nsundered from one another more or less sharply, who go to make up the\r\npeople of the Philippine Islands, contain many elements of good, and\r\nsome elements which we have a right to hope stand for progress. At\r\npresent they are utterly incapable of existing in independence at all or\r\nof building up a civilization of their own. I firmly believe that we can\r\nhelp them to rise higher and higher in the scale of civilization and of\r\ncapacity for self-government, and I most earnestly hope that in the end\r\nthey will be able to stand, if not entirely alone, yet in some such\r\nrelation to the United States as Cuba now stands. This end is not yet in\r\nsight, and it may be indefinitely postponed if our people are foolish\r\nenough to turn the attention of the Filipinos away from the problems of\r\nachieving moral and material prosperity, of working for a stable,\r\norderly, and just government, and toward foolish and dangerous intrigues\r\nfor a complete independence for which they are as yet totally unfit.\r\n\r\nOn the other hand our people must keep steadily before their minds the\r\nfact that the justification for our stay in the Philippines must\r\nultimately rest chiefly upon the good we are able to do in the islands.\r\nI do not overlook the fact that in the development of our interests in\r\nthe Pacific Ocean and along its coasts, the Philippines have played and\r\nwill play an important part; and that our interests have been served in\r\nmore than one way by the possession of the islands. But our chief reason\r\nfor continuing to hold them must be that we ought in good faith to try\r\nto do our share of the world's work, and this particular piece of work\r\nhas been imposed upon us by the results of the war with Spain. The\r\nproblem presented to us in the Philippine Islands is akin to, but not\r\nexactly like, the problems presented to the other great civilized powers\r\nwhich have possessions in the Orient. There are points of resemblance in\r\nour work to the work which is being done by the British in India and\r\nEgypt, by the French in Algiers, by the Dutch in Java, by the Russians\r\nin Turkestan, by the Japanese in Formosa; but more distinctly than any\r\nof these powers we are endeavoring to develop the natives themselves so\r\nthat they shall take an ever-increasing share in their own government,\r\nand as far as is prudent we are already admitting their representatives\r\nto a governmental equality with our own. There are commissioners,\r\njudges, and governors in the islands who are Filipinos and who have\r\nexactly the same share in the government of the islands as have their\r\ncolleagues who are Americans, while in the lower ranks, of course, the\r\ngreat majority of the public servants are Filipinos. Within two years we\r\nshall be trying the experiment of an elective lower house in the\r\nPhilippine legislature. It may be that the Filipinos will misuse this\r\nlegislature, and they certainly will misuse it if they are misled by\r\nfoolish persons here at home into starting an agitation for their own\r\nindependence or into any factious or improper action. In such case they\r\nwill do themselves no good and will stop for the time being all further\r\neffort to advance them and give them a greater share in their own\r\ngovernment. But if they act with wisdom and self-restraint, if they show\r\nthat they are capable of electing a legislature which in its turn is\r\ncapable of taking a sane and efficient part in the actual work of\r\ngovernment, they can rest assured that a full and increasing measure of\r\nrecognition will be given them. Above all they should remember that\r\ntheir prime needs are moral and industrial, not political. It is a good\r\nthing to try the experiment of giving them a legislature; but it is a\r\nfar better thing to give them schools, good roads, railroads which will\r\nenable them to get their products to market, honest courts, an honest\r\nand efficient constabulary, and all that tends to produce order, peace,\r\nfair dealing as between man and man, and habits of intelligent industry\r\nand thrift. If they are safeguarded against oppression, and if their\r\nreal wants, material and spiritual, are studied intelligently and in a\r\nspirit of friendly sympathy, much more good will be done them than by\r\nany effort to give them political power, though this effort may in its\r\nown proper time and place be proper enough.\r\n\r\nMeanwhile our own people should remember that there is need for the\r\nhighest standard of conduct among the Americans sent to the Philippine\r\nIslands, not only among the public servants but among the private\r\nindividuals who go to them. It is because I feel this so deeply that in\r\nthe administration of these islands I have positively refused to permit\r\nany discrimination whatsoever for political reasons and have insisted\r\nthat in choosing the public servants consideration should be paid solely\r\nto the worth of the men chosen and to the needs of the islands. There is\r\nno higher body of men in our public service than we have in the\r\nPhilippine Islands under Governor Wright and his associates. So far as\r\npossible these men should be given a free hand, and their suggestions\r\nshould receive the hearty backing both of the Executive and of the\r\nCongress. There is need of a vigilant and disinterested support of our\r\npublic servants in the Philippines by good citizens here in the United\r\nStates. Unfortunately hitherto those of our people here at home who have\r\nspecially claimed to be the champions of the Filipinos have in reality\r\nbeen their worst enemies. This will continue to be the case as long as\r\nthey strive to make the Filipinos independent, and stop all industrial\r\ndevelopment of the islands by crying out against the laws which would\r\nbring it on the ground that capitalists must not \"exploit\" the islands.\r\nSuch proceedings are not only unwise, but are most harmful to the\r\nFilipinos, who do not need independence at all, but who do need good\r\nlaws, good public servants, and the industrial development that can only\r\ncome if the investment, of American and foreign capital in the islands\r\nis favored in all legitimate ways.\r\n\r\nEvery measure taken concerning the islands should be taken primarily\r\nwith a view to their advantage. We should certainly give them lower\r\ntariff rates on their exports to the United States; if this is not done\r\nit will be a wrong to extend our shipping laws to them. I earnestly hope\r\nfor the immediate enactment into law of the legislation now pending to\r\nencourage American capital to seek investment in the islands in\r\nrailroads, in factories, in plantations, and in lumbering and mining.\r\n\r"

[1] "Mr. Speaker, Mr. President, distinguished Members of the Congress,\nhonored guests, and fellow citizens:\n\nToday marks my first State of the Union address to you, a constitutional\nduty as old as our Republic itself.\n\nPresident Washington began this tradition in 1790 after reminding the\nNation that the destiny of self-government and the \"preservation of the\nsacred fire of liberty\" is \"finally staked on the experiment entrusted\nto the hands of the American people.\" For our friends in the press, who\nplace a high premium on accuracy, let me say: I did not actually hear\nGeorge Washington say that. But it is a matter of historic record.\n\nBut from this podium, Winston Churchill asked the free world to stand\ntogether against the onslaught of aggression. Franklin Delano Roosevelt\nspoke of a day of infamy and summoned a nation to arms. Douglas\nMacArthur made an unforgettable farewell to a country he loved and\nserved so well. Dwight Eisenhower reminded us that peace was purchased\nonly at the price of strength. And John F. Kennedy spoke of the burden\nand glory that is freedom.\n\nWhen I visited this Chamber last year as a newcomer to Washington,\ncritical of past policies which I believed had failed, I proposed a new\nspirit of partnership between this Congress and this administration and\nbetween Washington and our State and local governments. In forging this\nnew partnership for America, we could achieve the oldest hopes of our\nRepublic--prosperity for our nation, peace for the world, and the\nblessings of individual liberty for our children and, someday, for all\nof humanity.\n\nIt's my duty to report to you tonight on the progress that we have made\nin our relations with other nations, on the foundation we've carefully\nlaid for our economic recovery, and finally, on a bold and spirited\ninitiative that I believe can change the face of American government and\nmake it again the servant of the people.\n\nSeldom have the stakes been higher for America. What we do and say here\nwill make all the difference to autoworkers in Detroit, lumberjacks in\nthe Northwest, steelworkers in Steubenville who are in the unemployment\nlines; to black teenagers in Newark and Chicago; to hard-pressed farmers\nand small businessmen; and to millions of everyday Americans who harbor\nthe simple wish of a safe and financially secure future for their\nchildren. To understand the state of the Union, we must look not only at\nwhere we are and where we're going but where we've been. The situation\nat this time last year was truly ominous.\n\nThe last decade has seen a series of recessions. There was a recession\nin 1970, in 1974, and again in the spring of 1980. Each time,\nunemployment increased and inflation soon turned up again. We coined the\nword \"stagflation\" to describe this.\n\nGovernment's response to these recessions was to pump up the money\nsupply and increase spending. In the last 6 months of 1980, as an\nexample, the money supply increased at the fastest rate in postwar\nhistory--13 percent. Inflation remained in double digits, and government\nspending increased at an annual rate of 17 percent. Interest rates\nreached a staggering 21.5 percent. There were 8 million unemployed.\n\nLate in 1981 we sank into the present recession, largely because\ncontinued high interest rates hurt the auto industry and construction.\nAnd there was a drop in productivity, and the already high unemployment\nincreased.\n\nThis time, however, things are different. We have an economic program in\nplace, completely different from the artificial quick fixes of the past.\nIt calls for a reduction of the rate of increase in government spending,\nand already that rate has been cut nearly in half. But reduced spending\nthe first and smallest phase of a 3-year tax rate reduction designed to\nstimulate the economy and create jobs. Already interest rates are down\nto 15 3/4 percent, but they must still go lower. Inflation is down from\n12.4 percent to 8.9, and for the month of December it was running at an\nannualized rate of 5.2 percent. If we had not acted as we did, things\nwould be far worse for all Americans than they are today. Inflation,\ntaxes, and interest rates would all be higher.\n\nA year ago, Americans' faith in their governmental process was steadily\ndeclining. Six out of 10 Americans were saying they were pessimistic\nabout their future. A new kind of defeatism was heard. Some said our\ndomestic problems were uncontrollable, that we had to learn to live with\nthis seemingly endless cycle of high inflation and high unemployment.\n\nThere were also pessimistic predictions about the relationship between\nour administration and this Congress. It was said we could never work\ntogether. Well, those predictions were wrong. The record is clear, and I\nbelieve that history will remember this as an era of American renewal,\nremember this administration as an administration of change, and\nremember this Congress as a Congress of destiny.\n\nTogether, we not only cut the increase in government spending nearly in\nhalf, we brought about the largest tax reductions and the most sweeping\nchanges in our tax structure since the beginning of this century. And\nbecause we indexed future taxes to the rate of inflation, we took away\ngovernment's built-in profit on inflation and its hidden incentive to\ngrow larger at the expense of American workers.\n\nTogether, after 50 years of taking power away from the hands of the\npeople in their States and local communities, we have started returning\npower and resources to them.\n\nTogether, we have cut the growth of new Federal regulations nearly in\nhalf. In 1981 there were 23,000 fewer pages in the Federal Register,\nwhich lists new regulations, than there were in 1980. By deregulating\noil we've come closer to achieving energy independence and helped bring\ndown the cost of gasoline and heating fuel.\n\nTogether, we have created an effective Federal strike force to combat\nwaste and fraud in government. In just 6 months it has saved the\ntaxpayers more than $2 billion, and it's only getting started.\n\nTogether we've begun to mobilize the private sector, not to duplicate\nwasteful and discredited government programs, but to bring thousands of\nAmericans into a volunteer effort to help solve many of America's social\nproblems.\n\nTogether we've begun to restore that margin of military safety that\nensures peace. Our country's uniform is being worn once again with\npride.\n\nTogether we have made a New Beginning, but we have only begun.\n\nNo one pretends that the way ahead will be easy. In my Inaugural Address\nlast year, I warned that the \"ills we suffer have come upon us over\nseveral decades. They will not go away in days, weeks, or months, but\nthey will go away . . . because we as Americans have the capacity now,\nas we've had it in the past, to do whatever needs to be done to preserve\nthis last and greatest bastion of freedom.\"\n\nThe economy will face difficult moments in the months ahead. But the\nprogram for economic recovery that is in place will pull the economy out\nof its slump and put us on the road to prosperity and stable growth by\nthe latter half of this year. And that is why I can report to you\ntonight that in the near future the state of the Union and the economy\nwill be better--much better--if we summon the strength to continue on\nthe course that we've charted.\n\nAnd so, the question: If the fundamentals are in place, what now? Well,\ntwo things. First, we must understand what's happening at the moment to\nthe economy. Our current problems are not the product of the recovery\nprogram that's only just now getting underway, as some would have you\nbelieve; they are the inheritance of decades of tax and tax and spend\nand spend.\n\nSecond, because our economic problems are deeply rooted and will not\nrespond to quick political fixes, we must stick to our carefully\nintegrated plan for recovery. That plan is based on four commonsense\nfundamentals: continued reduction of the growth in Federal spending;\npreserving the individual and business tax reductions that will\nstimulate saving and investment; removing unnecessary Federal\nregulations to spark productivity; and maintaining a healthy dollar and\na stable monetary policy, the latter a responsibility of the Federal\nReserve System.\n\nThe only alternative being offered to this economic program is a return\nto the policies that gave us a trillion-dollar debt, runaway inflation,\nrunaway interest rates and unemployment. The doubters would have us turn\nback the clock with tax increases that would offset the personal tax\nrate reductions already passed by this Congress. Raise present taxes to\ncut future deficits, they tell us. Well, I don't believe we should buy\nthat argument.\n\nThere are too many imponderables for anyone to predict deficits or\nsurpluses several years ahead with any degree of accuracy. The budget in\nplace, when I took office, had been projected as balanced. It turned out\nto have one of the biggest deficits in history. Another example of the\nimponderables that can make deficit projections highly questionable--a\nchange of only one percentage point in unemployment can alter a deficit\nup or down by some $25 billion.\n\nAs it now stands, our forecast, which we're required by law to make,\nwill show major deficits starting at less than a hundred billion dollars\nand declining, but still too high. More important, we're making progress\nwith the three keys to reducing deficits: economic growth, lower\ninterest rates, and spending control. The policies we have in place will\nreduce the deficit steadily, surely, and in time, completely.\n\nHigher taxes would not mean lower deficits. If they did, how would we\nexplain that tax revenues more than doubled just since 1976; yet in that\nsame 6-year period we ran the largest series of deficits in our history.\nIn 1980 tax revenues increased by $54 billion, and in 1980 we had one of\nour all-time biggest deficits. Raising taxes won't balance the budget;\nit will encourage more government spending and less private investment.\nRaising taxes will slow economic growth, reduce production, and destroy\nfuture jobs, making it more difficult for those without jobs to find\nthem and more likely that those who now have jobs could lose them. So, I\nwill not ask you to try to balance the budget on the backs of the\nAmerican taxpayers.\n\nI will seek no tax increases this year, and I have no intention of\nretreating from our basic program of tax relief. I promise to bring the\nAmerican people--to bring their tax rates down and to keep them down, to\nprovide them incentives to rebuild our economy, to save, to invest in\nAmerica's future. I will stand by my word. Tonight I'm urging the\nAmerican people: Seize these new opportunities to produce, to save, to\ninvest, and together we'll make this economy a mighty engine of freedom,\nhope, and prosperity again.\n\nNow, the budget deficit this year will exceed our earlier expectations.\nThe recession did that. It lowered revenues and increased costs. To some\nextent, we're also victims of our own success. We've brought inflation\ndown faster than we thought we could, and in doing this, we've deprived\ngovernment of those hidden revenues that occur when inflation pushes\npeople into higher income tax brackets. And the continued high interest\nrates last year cost the government about $5 billion more than\nanticipated.\n\nWe must cut out more nonessential government spending and rout out more\nwaste, and we will continue our efforts to reduce the number of\nemployees in the Federal work force by 75,000.\n\nThe budget plan I submit to you on February 8th will realize major\nsavings by dismantling the Departments of Energy and Education and by\neliminating ineffective subsidies for business. We'll continue to\nredirect our resources to our two highest budget priorities--a strong\nnational defense to keep America free and at peace and a reliable safety\nnet of social programs for those who have contributed and those who are\nin need.\n\nContrary to some of the wild charges you may have heard, this\nadministration has not and will not turn its back on America's elderly\nor America's poor. Under the new budget, funding for social insurance\nprograms will be more than double the amount spent only 6 years ago. But\nit would be foolish to pretend that these or any programs cannot be made\nmore efficient and economical.\n\nThe entitlement programs that make up our safety net for the truly needy\nhave worthy goals and many deserving recipients. We will protect them.\nBut there's only one way to see to it that these programs really help\nthose whom they were designed to help. And that is to bring their\nspiraling costs under control.\n\nToday we face the absurd situation of a Federal budget with\nthree-quarters of its expenditures routinely referred to as\n\"uncontrollable.\" And a large part of this goes to entitlement programs.\n\nCommittee after committee of this Congress has heard witness after\nwitness describe many of these programs as poorly administered and rife\nwith waste and fraud. Virtually every American who shops in a local\nsupermarket is aware of the daily abuses that take place in the food\nstamp program, which has grown by 16,000 percent in the last 15 years.\nAnother example is Medicare and Medicaid--programs with worthy goals but\nwhose costs have increased from 11.2 billion to almost 60 billion, more\nthan 5 times as much, in just 10 years.\n\nWaste and fraud are serious problems. Back in 1980 Federal investigators\ntestified before one of your committees that \"corruption has permeated\nvirtually every area of the Medicare and Medicaid health care industry.\"\nOne official said many of the people who are cheating the system were\n\"very confident that nothing was going to happen to them.\" Well,\nsomething is going to happen. Not only the taxpayers are defrauded; the\npeople with real dependency on these programs are deprived of what they\nneed, because available resources are going not to the needy, but to the\ngreedy.\n\nThe time has come to control the uncontrollable. In August we made a\nstart. I signed a bill to reduce the growth of these programs by $44\nbillion over the next 3 years while at the same time preserving\nessential services for the truly needy. Shortly you will receive from me\na message on further reforms we intend to install--some new, but others\nlong recommended by your own congressional committees. I ask you to help\nmake these savings for the American taxpayer.\n\nThe savings we propose in entitlement programs will total some $63\nbillion over 4 Years and will, without affecting social t security, go a\nlong way toward bringing Federal spending under control.\n\nBut don't be fooled by those who proclaim that spending cuts will\ndeprive the elderly, the needy, and the helpless. The. Federal\nGovernment will still subsidize 95 million meals every day. That's one\nout of seven of all the meals served in America. Head Start, senior\nnutrition programs, and child welfare programs will not be cut from the\nlevels we proposed last year. More than one-half billion dollars has\nbeen proposed for minority business assistance. And research at the\nNational Institute of Health will be increased by over $100 million.\nWhile meeting all these needs, we intend to plug unwarranted tax\nloopholes and strengthen the law which requires all large corporations\nto pay a minimum tax.\n\nI am confident the economic program we've put into operation will\nprotect the needy while it triggers a recovery that will benefit all\nAmericans. It will stimulate the economy, result in increased savings\nand provide capital for expansion, mortgages for homebuilding, and jobs\nfor the unemployed.\n\nNow that the essentials of that program are in place, our next major\nundertaking must be a program--just as bold, just as innovative--to make\ngovernment again accountable to the people, to make our system of\nfederalism work again.\n\nOur citizens feel they've lost control of even the most basic decisions\nmade about the essential services of government, such as schools,\nwelfare, roads, and even garbage collection. And they're right. A maze\nof interlocking jurisdictions and levels of government confronts average\ncitizens in trying to solve even the simplest of problems. They don't\nknow where to turn for answers, who to hold accountable, who to praise,\nwho to blame, who to vote for or against. The main reason for this is\nthe overpowering growth of Federal grants-in-aid programs during the\npast few decades.\n\nIn 1960 the Federal Government had 132 categorical grant programs,\ncosting $7 billion. When I took office, there were approximately 500,\ncosting nearly a hundred billion dollars--13 programs for energy, 36 for\npollution control, 66 for social services, 90 for education. And here in\nthe Congress, it takes at least 166 committees just to try to keep track\nof them.\n\nYou know and I know that neither the President nor the Congress can\nproperly oversee this jungle of grants-in-aid; indeed, the growth of\nthese grants has led to the distortion in the vital functions of\ngovernment. As one Democratic Governor put it recently: The National\nGovernment should be worrying about \"arms control, not potholes.\"\n\nThe growth in these Federal programs has--in the words of one\nintergovernmental commission--made the Federal Government \"more\npervasive, more intrusive, more unmanageable, more ineffective and\ncostly, and above all, more (un) accountable.\" Let's solve this problem\nwith a single, bold stroke: the return of some $47 billion in Federal\nprograms to State and local government, together with the means to\nfinance them and a transition period of nearly 10 years to avoid\nunnecessary disruption.\n\nI will shortly send this Congress a message describing this program. I\nwant to emphasize, however, that its full details will have been worked\nout only after close consultation with congressional, State, and local\nofficials.\n\nStarting in fiscal 1984, the Federal Government will assume full\nresponsibility for the cost of the rapidly growing Medicaid program to\ngo along with its existing responsibility for Medicare. As part of a\nfinancially equal swap, the States will simultaneously take full\nresponsibility for Aid to Families with Dependent Children and food\nstamps. This will make welfare less costly and more responsive to\ngenuine need, because it'll be designed and administered closer to the\ngrass roots and the people it serves.\n\nIn 1984 the Federal Government will apply the full proceeds from certain\nexcise taxes to a grass roots trust fund that will belong in fair shares\nto the 50 States. The total amount flowing into this fund will be $28\nbillion a year. Over the next 4 years the States can use this money in\neither of two ways. If they want to continue receiving Federal grants in\nsuch areas as transportation, education, and social services, they can\nuse their trust fund money to pay for the grants. Or to the extent they\nchoose to forgo the Federal grant programs, they can use their trust\nfund money on their own for those or other purposes. There will be a\nmandatory pass-through of part of these funds to local governments.\n\nBy 1988 the States will be in complete control of over 40 Federal grant\nprograms. The trust fund will start to phase out, eventually to\ndisappear, and the excise taxes will be turned over to the States. They\ncan then preserve, lower, or raise taxes on their own and fund and\nmanage these programs as they see fit.\n\nIn a single stroke we will be accomplishing a realignment that will end\ncumbersome administration and spiraling costs at the Federal level while\nwe ensure these programs will be more responsive to both the people\nthey're meant to help and the people who pay for them.\n\nHand in hand with this program to strengthen the discretion and\nflexibility of State and local governments, we're proposing legislation\nfor an experimental effort to improve and develop our depressed urban\nareas in the 1980's and '90's. This legislation will permit States and\nlocalities to apply to the Federal Government for designation as urban\nenterprise zones. A broad range of special economic incentives in the\nzones will help attract new business, new jobs, new opportunity to\nAmerica's inner cities and rural towns. Some will say our mission is to\nsave free enterprise. Well, I say we must free enterprise so that\ntogether we can save America.\n\nSome will also say our States and local communities are not up to the\nchallenge of a new and creative partnership. Well, that might have been\ntrue 20 years ago before reforms like reapportionment and the Voting\nRights Act, the 10-year extension of which I strongly support. It's no\nlonger true today. This administration has faith in State and local\ngovernments and the constitutional balance envisioned by the Founding\nFathers. We also believe in the integrity, decency, and sound, good\nsense of grass roots Americans.\n\nOur faith in the American people is reflected in another major endeavor.\nOur private sector initiatives task force is seeking out successful\ncommunity models of school, church, business, union, foundation, and\ncivic programs that help community needs. Such groups are almost\ninvariably far more efficient than government in running social\nprograms.\n\nWe're not asking them to replace discarded and often discredited\ngovernment programs dollar for dollar, service for service. We just want\nto help them perform the good works they choose and help others to\nprofit by their example. Three hundred and eighty-five thousand\ncorporations and private organizations are already working on social\nprograms ranging from drug rehabilitation to job training, and thousands\nmore Americans have written us asking how they can help. The volunteer\nspirit is still alive and well in America.\n\nOur nation's long journey towards civil rights for all our\ncitizens--once a source of discord, now a source of pride--must continue\nwith no backsliding or slowing down. We must and shall see that those\nbasic laws that guarantee equal rights are preserved and, when\nnecessary, strengthened.\n\nOur concern for equal rights for women is firm and unshakable. We\nlaunched a new Task Force on Legal Equity for Women and a Fifty States\nProject that will examine State laws for discriminatory language. And\nfor the first time in our history, a woman sits on the highest court in\nthe land.\n\nSo, too, the problem of crime--one as real and deadly serious as any in\nAmerica today. It demands that we seek transformation of our legal\nsystem, which overly protects the rights of criminals while it leaves\nsociety and the innocent victims of crime without justice.\n\nWe look forward to the enactment of a responsible clean air act to\nincrease jobs while continuing to improve the quality of our air. We're\nencouraged by the bipartisan initiative of the House and are hopeful of\nfurther progress as the Senate continues its deliberations.\n\nSo far, I've concentrated largely, now, on domestic matters. To view the\nstate of the Union in perspective, we must not ignore the rest of the\nworld. There isn't time tonight for a lengthy treatment of social--or\nforeign policy, I should say, a subject I intend to address in detail in\nthe near future. A few words, however, are in order on the progress\nwe've made over the past year, reestablishing respect for our nation\naround the globe and some of the challenges and goals that we will\napproach in the year ahead.\n\nAt Ottawa and Cancun, I met with leaders of the major industrial powers\nand developing nations. Now, some of those I met with were a little\nsurprised that I didn't apologize for America's wealth. Instead, I spoke\nof the strength of the free marketplace system and how that system could\nhelp them realize their aspirations for economic development and\npolitical freedom. I believe lasting friendships were made, and the\nfoundation was laid for future cooperation.\n\nIn the vital region of the Caribbean Basin, we're developing a program\nof aid, trade, and investment incentives to promote self-sustaining\ngrowth and a better, more secure life for our neighbors to the south.\nToward those who would export terrorism and subversion in the Caribbean\nand elsewhere, especially Cuba and Libya, we will act with firmness.\n\nOur foreign policy is a policy of strength, fairness, and balance. By\nrestoring America's military credibility, by pursuing peace at the\nnegotiating table wherever both sides are willing to sit down in good\nfaith, and by regaining the respect of America's allies and adversaries\nalike, we have strengthened our country's position as a force for peace\nand progress in the world.\n\nWhen action is called for, we're taking it. Our sanctions against the\nmilitary dictatorship that has attempted to crush human rights in\nPoland--and against the Soviet regime behind that military\ndictatorship--clearly demonstrated to the world that America will not\nconduct \"business as usual\" with the forces of oppression. If the events\nin Poland continue to deteriorate, further measures will follow.\n\nNow, let me also note that private American groups have taken the lead\nin making January 30th a day of solidarity with the people of Poland.\nSo, too, the European Parliament has called for March 21st to be an\ninternational day of support for Afghanistan. Well, I urge all\npeace-loving peoples to join together on those days, to raise their\nvoices, to speak and pray for freedom.\n\nMeanwhile, we're working for reduction of arms and military activities,\nas I announced in my address to the Nation last November 18th. We have\nproposed to the Soviet Union a far-reaching agenda for mutual reduction\nof military forces and have already initiated negotiations with them in\nGeneva on intermediate-range nuclear forces. In those talks it is\nessential that we negotiate from a position of strength. There must be a\nreal incentive for the Soviets to take these talks seriously. This\nrequires that we rebuild our defenses.\n\nIn the last decade, while we sought the moderation of Soviet power\nthrough a process of restraint and accommodation, the Soviets engaged in\nan unrelenting buildup of their military forces. The protection of our\nnational security has required that we undertake a substantial program\nto enhance our military forces.\n\nWe have not neglected to strengthen our traditional alliances in Europe\nand Asia, or to develop key relationships with our partners in the\nMiddle East and other countries. Building a more peaceful world requires\na sound strategy and the national resolve to back it up. When radical\nforces threaten our friends, when economic misfortune creates conditions\nof instability, when strategically vital parts of the world fall under\nthe shadow of Soviet power, our response can make the difference between\npeaceful change or disorder and violence. That's why we've laid such\nstress not only on our own defense but on our vital foreign assistance\nprogram. Your recent passage of the Foreign Assistance Act sent a signal\nto the world that America will not shrink from making the investments\nnecessary for both peace and security. Our foreign policy must be rooted\nin realism, not naivete or self-delusion.\n\nA recognition of what the Soviet empire is about is the starting point.\nWinston Churchill, in negotiating with the Soviets, observed that they\nrespect only strength and resolve in their dealings with other nations.\nThat's why we've moved to reconstruct our national defenses. We intend\nto keep the peace. We will also keep our freedom.\n\nWe have made pledges of a new frankness in our public statements and\nworldwide broadcasts. In the face of a climate of falsehood and\nmisinformation, we've promised the world a season of truth--the truth of\nour great civilized ideas: individual liberty, representative\ngovernment, the rule of law under God. We've never needed walls or\nminefields or barbed wire to keep our people in. Nor do we declare\nmartial law to keep our people from voting for the kind of government\nthey want.\n\nYes, we have our problems; yes, we're in a time of recession. And it's\ntrue, there's no quick fix, as I said, to instantly end the tragic pain\nof unemployment. But we will end it. The process has already begun, and\nwe'll see its effect as the year goes on.\n\nWe speak with pride and admiration of that little band of Americans who\novercame insuperable odds to set this nation on course 200 years ago.\nBut our glory didn't end with them. Americans ever since have emulated\ntheir deeds.\n\nWe don't have to turn to our history books for heroes. They're all\naround us. One who sits among you here tonight epitomized that heroism\nat the end of the longest imprisonment ever inflicted on men of our\nArmed Forces. Who will ever forget that night when we waited for\ntelevision to bring us the scene of that first plane landing at Clark\nField in the Philippines, bringing our POW's home? The plane door opened\nand Jeremiah Denton came slowly down the ramp. He caught sight of our\nflag, saluted it, said, \"God bless America,\" and then thanked us for\nbringing him home.\n\nJust 2 weeks ago, in the midst of a terrible tragedy on the Potomac, we\nsaw again the spirit of American heroism at its finest--the heroism of\ndedicated rescue workers saving crash victims from icy waters. And we\nsaw the heroism of one of our young government employees, Lenny Skutnik,\nwho, when he saw a woman lose her grip on the helicopter line, dived\ninto the water and dragged her to safety.\n\nAnd then there are countless, quiet, everyday heroes of American who\nsacrifice long and hard so their children will know a better life than\nthey've known; church and civic volunteers who help to feed, clothe,\nnurse, and teach the needy; millions who've made our nation and our\nnation's destiny so very special--unsung heroes who may not have\nrealized their own dreams themselves but then who reinvest those dreams\nin their children. Don't let anyone tell you that America's best days\nare behind her, that the American spirit has been vanquished. We've seen\nit triumph too often in our lives to stop believing in it now.\n\nA hundred and twenty years ago, the greatest of all our Presidents\ndelivered his second State of the Union message in this Chamber. \"We\ncannot escape history,\" Abraham Lincoln warned. \"We of this Congress and\nthis administration will be remembered in spite of ourselves.\" The\n\"trial through which we pass will light us down, in honor or dishonor,\nto the latest (last) generation.\"\n\nWell, that President and that Congress did not fail the American people.\nTogether they weathered the storm and preserved the Union. Let it be\nsaid of us that we, too, did not fail; that we, too, worked together to\nbring America through difficult times. Let us so conduct ourselves that\ntwo centuries from now, another Congress and another President, meeting\nin this Chamber as we are meeting, will speak of us with pride, saying\nthat we met the test and preserved for them in their day the sacred\nflame of liberty--this last, best hope of man on Earth.\n\nGod bless you, and thank you.\n\nNOTE: The President spoke at 9 p.m. in the House Chamber at the Capitol.\nHe was introduced by Thomas P. O'Neill, Jr., Speaker of the House of\nRepresentatives. The address was broadcast live on nationwide radio and\ntelevision.\n"
