[1] "Mr. Speaker, Vice President Cheney, Members of Congress, distinguished\nguests, fellow citizens:\n\nEvery year, by law and by custom, we meet here to consider the state of\nthe union. This year, we gather in this chamber deeply aware of decisive\ndays that lie ahead.\n\nYou and I serve our country in a time of great consequence. During this\nsession of Congress, we have the duty to reform domestic programs vital\nto our country...and we have the opportunity to save millions of lives\nabroad from a terrible disease. We will work for a prosperity that is\nbroadly shared...and we will answer every danger and every enemy that\nthreatens the American people.\n\nIn all these days of promise and days of reckoning, we can be confident.\nIn a whirlwind of change, and hope, and peril, our faith is sure, our\nresolve is firm, and our union is strong.\n\nThis country has many challenges. We will not deny, we will not ignore,\nwe will not pass along our problems to other Congresses, other\npresidents, and other generations. We will confront them with focus, and\nclarity, and courage.\n\nDuring the last two years, we have seen what can be accomplished when we\nwork together. To lift the standards of our public schools, we achieved\nhistoric education reform - which must now be carried out in every\nschool, and every classroom, so that every child in America can read,\nand learn, and succeed in life. To protect our country, we reorganized\nour government and created the Department of Homeland Security - which\nis mobilizing against the threats of a new era. To bring our economy out\nof recession, we delivered the largest tax relief in a generation. To\ninsist on integrity in American business, we passed tough reforms, and\nwe are holding corporate criminals to account.\n\nSome might call this a good record. I call it a good start. Tonight I\nask the House and Senate to join me in the next bold steps to serve our\nfellow citizens.\n\nOur first goal is clear: We must have an economy that grows fast enough\nto employ every man and woman who seeks a job.\n\nAfter recession, terrorist attacks, corporate scandals, and stock market\ndeclines, our economy is recovering - yet it is not growing fast enough,\nor strongly enough. With unemployment rising, our Nation needs more\nsmall businesses to open, more companies to invest and expand, more\nemployers to put up the sign that says, \"Help Wanted.\"\n\nJobs are created when the economy grows; the economy grows when\nAmericans have more money to spend and invest; and the best, fairest way\nto make sure Americans have that money is not to tax it away in the\nfirst place.\n\nI am proposing that all the income tax reductions set for 2004 and 2006\nbe made permanent and effective this year. And under my plan, as soon as\nI have signed the bill, this extra money will start showing up in\nworkers' paychecks. Instead of gradually reducing the marriage penalty,\nwe should do it now. Instead of slowly raising the child credit to a\nthousand dollars, we should send the checks to American families now.\n\nThis tax relief is for everyone who pays income taxes - and it will help\nour economy immediately. Ninety-two million Americans will keep - this\nyear - an average of almost 1,100 dollars more of their own money. A\nfamily of four with an income of 40,000 dollars would see their federal\nincome taxes fall from 1,178 dollars to 45 dollars per year. And our\nplan will improve the bottom line for more than 23 million small\nbusinesses.\n\nYou, the Congress, have already passed all these reductions, and\npromised them for future years. If this tax relief is good for Americans\nthree, or five, or seven years from now, it is even better for Americans\ntoday.\n\nWe also strengthen the economy by treating investors equally in our tax\nlaws. It is fair to tax a company's profits. It is not fair to again tax\nthe shareholder on the same profits. To boost investor confidence, and\nto help the nearly 10 million seniors who receive dividend income, I ask\nyou to end the unfair double taxation of dividends.\n\nLower taxes and greater investment will help this economy expand. More\njobs mean more taxpayers - and higher revenues to our government. The\nbest way to address the deficit and move toward a balanced budget is to\nencourage economic growth - and to show some spending discipline in\nWashington, D.C. We must work together to fund only our most important\npriorities. I will send you a budget that increases discretionary\nspending by four percent next year - about as much as the average\nfamily's income is expected to grow. And that is a good benchmark for\nus: Federal spending should not rise any faster than the paychecks of\nAmerican families.\n\nA growing economy, and a focus on essential priorities, will also be\ncrucial to the future of Social Security. As we continue to work\ntogether to keep Social Security sound and reliable, we must offer\nyounger workers a chance to invest in retirement accounts that they will\ncontrol and they will own.\n\nOur second goal is high quality, affordable health care for all\nAmericans.\n\nThe American system of medicine is a model of skill and innovation -\nwith a pace of discovery that is adding good years to our lives. Yet for\nmany people, medical care costs too much - and many have no coverage at\nall. These problems will not be solved with a nationalized health care\nsystem that dictates coverage and rations care. Instead, we must work\ntoward a system in which all Americans have a good insurance\npolicy...choose their own doctors..and seniors and low-income Americans\nreceive the help they need. Instead of bureaucrats, and trial lawyers,\nand HMOs, we must put doctors, and nurses, and patients back in charge\nof American medicine.\n\nHealth care reform must begin with Medicare, because Medicare is the\nbinding commitment of a caring society. We must renew that commitment by\ngiving seniors access to the preventive medicine and new drugs that are\ntransforming health care in America.\n\nSeniors happy with the current Medicare system should be able to keep\ntheir coverage just the way it is. And just like you, the members of\nCongress, members of your staffs, and other federal employees, all\nseniors should have the choice of a health care plan that provides\nprescription drugs. My budget will commit an additional 400 billion\ndollars over the next decade to reform and strengthen Medicare. Leaders\nof both political parties have talked for years about strengthening\nMedicare - I urge the members of this new Congress to act this year.\n\nTo improve our health care system, we must address one of the prime\ncauses of higher costs - the constant threat that physicians and\nhospitals will be unfairly sued. Because of excessive litigation,\neverybody pays more for health care - and many parts of America are\nlosing fine doctors. No one has ever been healed by a frivolous lawsuit\n- and I urge the Congress to pass medical liability reform.\n\nOur third goal is to promote energy independence for our country, while\ndramatically improving the environment.\n\nI have sent you a comprehensive energy plan to promote energy efficiency\nand conservation, to develop cleaner technology, and to produce more\nenergy at home. I have sent you Clear Skies legislation that mandates a\n70 percent cut in air pollution from power plants over the next 15\nyears. I have sent you a Healthy Forests Initiative, to help prevent the\ncatastrophic fires that devastate communities, kill wildlife, and burn\naway millions of acres of treasured forest.\n\nI urge you to pass these measures, for the good of both our environment\nand our economy. Even more, I ask you to take a crucial step, and\nprotect our environment in ways that generations before us could not\nhave imagined. In this century, the greatest environmental progress will\ncome about, not through endless lawsuits or command and control\nregulations, but through technology and innovation. Tonight I am\nproposing 1.2 billion dollars in research funding so that America can\nlead the world in developing clean, hydrogen-powered automobiles.\n\nA simple chemical reaction between hydrogen and oxygen generates energy,\nwhich can be used to power a car - producing only water, not exhaust\nfumes. With a new national commitment, our scientists and engineers will\novercome obstacles to taking these cars from laboratory to showroom - so\nthat the first car driven by a child born today could be powered by\nhydrogen, and pollution-free. Join me in this important innovation - to\nmake our air significantly cleaner, and our country much less dependent\non foreign sources of energy.\n\nOur fourth goal is to apply the compassion of America to the deepest\nproblems of America. For so many in our country - the homeless, the\nfatherless, the addicted - the need is great. Yet there is power -\nwonder-working power - in the goodness, and idealism, and faith of the\nAmerican people.\n\nAmericans are doing the work of compassion every day - visiting\nprisoners, providing shelter to battered women, bringing companionship\nto lonely seniors. These good works deserve our praise...they deserve\nour personal support...and, when appropriate, they deserve the\nassistance of our government. I urge you to pass both my faith-based\ninitiative and the Citizen Service Act - to encourage acts of compassion\nthat can transform America, one heart and one soul at a time.\n\nLast year, I called on my fellow citizens to participate in USA Freedom\nCorps, which is enlisting tens of thousands of new volunteers across\nAmerica. Tonight I ask Congress and the American people to focus the\nspirit of service and the resources of government on the needs of some\nof our most vulnerable citizens - boys and girls trying to grow up\nwithout guidance and attention...and children who have to go through a\nprison gate to be hugged by their mom or dad. I propose a 450 million\ndollar initiative to bring mentors to more than a million disadvantaged\njunior high students and children of prisoners. Government will support\nthe training and recruiting of mentors, yet it is the men and women of\nAmerica who will fill the need. One mentor, one person, can change a\nlife forever - and I urge you to be that one person.\n\nAnother cause of hopelessness is addiction to drugs. Addiction crowds\nout friendship, ambition, moral conviction, and reduces all the richness\nof life to a single destructive desire. As a government, we are fighting\nillegal drugs by cutting off supplies, and reducing demand through\nanti-drug education programs. Yet for those already addicted, the fight\nagainst drugs is a fight for their own lives.\n\nToo many Americans in search of treatment cannot get it. So tonight I\npropose a new 600 million dollar program to help an additional 300,000\nAmericans receive treatment over the next three years.\n\nOur Nation is blessed with recovery programs that do amazing work. One\nof them is found at the Healing Place Church in Baton Rouge, Louisiana.\nA man in the program said, \"God does miracles in people .s lives, and\nyou never think it could be you.\" Tonight, let us bring to all Americans\nwho struggle with drug addiction this message of hope: The miracle of\nrecovery is possible, and it could be you.\n\nBy caring for children who need mentors, and for addicted men and women\nwho need treatment, we are building a more welcoming society - a culture\nthat values every life. And in this work we must not overlook the\nweakest among us. I ask you to protect infants at the very hour of\nbirth, and end the practice of partial-birth abortion. And because no\nhuman life should be started or ended as the object of an experiment, I\nask you to set a high standard for humanity and pass a law against all\nhuman cloning.\n\nThe qualities of courage and compassion that we strive for in America\nalso determine our conduct abroad. The American flag stands for more\nthan our power and our interests. Our Founders dedicated this country to\nthe cause of human dignity - the rights of every person and the\npossibilities of every life. This conviction leads us into the world to\nhelp the afflicted, and defend the peace, and confound the designs of\nevil men. In Afghanistan, we helped to liberate an oppressed\npeople...and we will continue helping them secure their country, rebuild\ntheir society, and educate all their children - boys and girls. In the\nMiddle East, we will continue to seek peace between a secure Israel and\na democratic Palestine. Across the earth, America is feeding the hungry;\nmore than 60 percent of international food aid comes as a gift from the\npeople of the United States.\n\nAs our Nation moves troops and builds alliances to make our world safer,\nwe must also remember our calling, as a blessed country, to make this\nworld better. Today, on the continent of Africa, nearly 30 million\npeople have the AIDS virus - including three million children under the\nage of 15. There are whole countries in Africa where more than one-third\nof the adult population carries the infection. More than four million\nrequire immediate drug treatment. Yet across that continent, only 50,000\nAIDS victims - only 50,000 - are receiving the medicine they need.\n\nBecause the AIDS diagnosis is considered a death sentence, many do not\nseek treatment. Almost all who do are turned away. A doctor in rural\nSouth Africa describes his frustration. He says, \"We have no\nmedicines..many hospitals tell [people], 'You've got AIDS. We can't help\nyou. Go home and die.' \"\n\nIn an age of miraculous medicines, no person should have to hear those\nwords. AIDS can be prevented. Anti-retroviral drugs can extend life for\nmany years. And the cost of those drugs has dropped from 12,000 dollars\na year to under 300 dollars a year - which places a tremendous\npossibility within our grasp.\n\nLadies and gentlemen, seldom has history offered a greater opportunity\nto do so much for so many. We have confronted, and will continue to\nconfront, HIV/AIDS in our own country. And to meet a severe and urgent\ncrisis abroad, tonight I propose the Emergency Plan for AIDS Relief - a\nwork of mercy beyond all current international efforts to help the\npeople of Africa. This comprehensive plan will prevent seven million new\nAIDS infections...treat at least two million people with life-extending\ndrugs...and provide humane care for millions of people suffering from\nAIDS, and for children orphaned by AIDS. I ask the Congress to commit 15\nbillion dollars over the next five years, including nearly ten billion\ndollars in new money, to turn the tide against AIDS in the most\nafflicted nations of Africa and the Caribbean.\n\nThis Nation can lead the world in sparing innocent people from a plague\nof nature. And this Nation is leading the world in confronting and\ndefeating the man-made evil of international terrorism.\n\nThere are days when the American people do not hear news about the war\non terror. There is never a day when I do not learn of another threat,\nor receive reports of operations in progress, or give an order in this\nglobal war against a scattered network of killers. The war goes on, and\nwe are winning.\n\nTo date we have arrested, or otherwise dealt with, many key commanders\nof al-Qaida. They include a man who directed logistics and funding for\nthe September 11th attacks...the chief of al-Qaida operations in the\nPersian Gulf who planned the bombings of our embassies in East Africa\nand the USS Cole...an al-Qaida operations chief from Southeast Asia...a\nformer director of al-Qaida's training camps in Afghanistan...a key\nal-Qaida operative in Europe..and a major al-Qaida leader in Yemen. All\ntold, more than 3,000 suspected terrorists have been arrested in many\ncountries. And many others have met a different fate. They are no longer\na problem for the United States and our friends and allies.\n\nWe are working closely with other nations to prevent further attacks.\nAmerica and coalition countries have uncovered and stopped terrorist\nconspiracies targeting the American embassy in Yemen...the American\nembassy in Singapore...a Saudi military base...and ships in the straits\nof Hormuz, and the straits of Gibraltar. We have broken al-Qaida cells\nin Hamburg, and Milan, and Madrid, and London, and Paris - as well as\nBuffalo, New York.\n\nWe have the terrorists on the run, and we are keeping them on the run.\nOne by one, the terrorists are learning the meaning of American justice.\n\nAs we fight this war, we will remember where it began - here, in our own\ncountry. This government is taking unprecedented measures to protect our\npeople and defend our homeland. We have intensified security at the\nborders and ports of entry...posted more than 50,000 newly trained\nfederal screeners in airports...begun inoculating troops and first\nresponders against smallpox...and are deploying the Nation's first early\nwarning network of sensors to detect biological attack. And this year,\nfor the first time, we are beginning to field a defense to protect this\nNation against ballistic missiles.\n\nI thank the Congress for supporting these measures. I ask you tonight to\nadd to our future security with a major research and production effort\nto guard our people against bio-terrorism, called Project Bioshield. The\nbudget I send you will propose almost six billion dollars to quickly\nmake available effective vaccines and treatments against agents like\nanthrax, botulinum toxin, Ebola, and plague. We must assume that our\nenemies would use these diseases as weapons, and we must act before the\ndangers are upon us.\n\nSince September 11th, our intelligence and law enforcement agencies have\nworked more closely than ever to track and disrupt the terrorists. The\nFBI is improving its ability to analyze intelligence, and transforming\nitself to meet new threats. And tonight, I am instructing the leaders of\nthe FBI, Central Intelligence, Homeland Security, and the Department of\nDefense to develop a Terrorist Threat Integration Center, to merge and\nanalyze all threat information in a single location. Our government must\nhave the very best information possible, and we will use it to make sure\nthe right people are in the right places to protect our citizens.\n\nOur war against terror is a contest of will, in which perseverance is\npower. In the ruins of two towers, at the western wall of the Pentagon,\non a field in Pennsylvania, this Nation made a pledge, and we renew that\npledge tonight: Whatever the duration of this struggle, and whatever the\ndifficulties, we will not permit the triumph of violence in the affairs\nof men...free people will set the course of history.\n\nToday, the gravest danger in the war on terror...the gravest danger\nfacing America and the world...is outlaw regimes that seek and possess\nnuclear, chemical, and biological weapons. These regimes could use such\nweapons for blackmail, terror, and mass murder. They could also give or\nsell those weapons to their terrorist allies, who would use them without\nthe least hesitation.\n\nThis threat is new; America's duty is familiar. Throughout the 20th\ncentury, small groups of men seized control of great nations...built\narmies and arsenals..and set out to dominate the weak and intimidate the\nworld. In each case, their ambitions of cruelty and murder had no limit.\nIn each case, the ambitions of Hitlerism, militarism, and communism were\ndefeated by the will of free peoples, by the strength of great\nalliances, and by the might of the United States of America. Now, in\nthis century, the ideology of power and domination has appeared again,\nand seeks to gain the ultimate weapons of terror. Once again, this\nNation and our friends are all that stand between a world at peace, and\na world of chaos and constant alarm. Once again, we are called to defend\nthe safety of our people, and the hopes of all mankind. And we accept\nthis responsibility.\n\nAmerica is making a broad and determined effort to confront these\ndangers. We have called on the United Nations to fulfill its charter,\nand stand by its demand that Iraq disarm. We are strongly supporting the\nInternational Atomic Energy Agency in its mission to track and control\nnuclear materials around the world. We are working with other\ngovernments to secure nuclear materials in the former Soviet Union, and\nto strengthen global treaties banning the production and shipment of\nmissile technologies and weapons of mass destruction.\n\nIn all of these efforts, however, America's purpose is more than to\nfollow a process - it is to achieve a result: the end of terrible\nthreats to the civilized world. All free nations have a stake in\npreventing sudden and catastrophic attack. We are asking them to join\nus, and many are doing so. Yet the course of this Nation does not depend\non the decisions of others. Whatever action is required, whenever action\nis necessary, I will defend the freedom and security of the American\npeople.\n\nDifferent threats require different strategies. In Iran, we continue to\nsee a government that represses its people, pursues weapons of mass\ndestruction, and supports terror. We also see Iranian citizens risking\nintimidation and death as they speak out for liberty, human rights, and\ndemocracy. Iranians, like all people, have a right to choose their own\ngovernment, and determine their own destiny - and the United States\nsupports their aspirations to live in freedom.\n\nOn the Korean peninsula, an oppressive regime rules a people living in\nfear and starvation. Throughout the 1990s, the United States relied on a\nnegotiated framework to keep North Korea from gaining nuclear weapons.\nWe now know that the regime was deceiving the world, and developing\nthose weapons all along. And today the North Korean regime is using its\nnuclear program to incite fear and seek concessions. America and the\nworld will not be blackmailed. America is working with the countries of\nthe region - South Korea, Japan, China, and Russia - to find a peaceful\nsolution, and to show the North Korean government that nuclear weapons\nwill bring only isolation, economic stagnation, and continued hardship.\nThe North Korean regime will find respect in the world, and revival for\nits people, only when it turns away from its nuclear ambitions.\n\nOur Nation and the world must learn the lessons of the Korean peninsula,\nand not allow an even greater threat to rise up in Iraq. A brutal\ndictator, with a history of reckless aggression..with ties to\nterrorism... with great potential wealth...will not be permitted to\ndominate a vital region and threaten the United States.\n\nTwelve years ago, Saddam Hussein faced the prospect of being the last\ncasualty in a war he had started and lost. To spare himself, he agreed\nto disarm of all weapons of mass destruction. For the next 12 years, he\nsystematically violated that agreement. He pursued chemical, biological,\nand nuclear weapons even while inspectors were in his country. Nothing\nto date has restrained him from his pursuit of these weapons - not\neconomic sanctions, not isolation from the civilized world, not even\ncruise missile strikes on his military facilities. Almost three months\nago, the United Nations Security Council gave Saddam Hussein his final\nchance to disarm. He has shown instead his utter contempt for the United\nNations, and for the opinion of the world.\n\nThe 108 UN weapons inspectors were not sent to conduct a scavenger hunt\nfor hidden materials across a country the size of California. The job of\nthe inspectors is to verify that Iraq's regime is disarming. It is up to\nIraq to show exactly where it is hiding its banned weapons...lay those\nweapons out for the world to see...and destroy them as directed. Nothing\nlike this has happened.\n\nThe United Nations concluded in 1999 that Saddam Hussein had biological\nweapons materials sufficient to produce over 25,000 liters of anthrax -\nenough doses to kill several million people. He has not accounted for\nthat material. He has given no evidence that he has destroyed it.\n\nThe United Nations concluded that Saddam Hussein had materials\nsufficient to produce more than 38,000 liters of botulinum toxin -\nenough to subject millions of people to death by respiratory failure. He\nhas not accounted for that material. He has given no evidence that he\nhas destroyed it.\n\nOur intelligence officials estimate that Saddam Hussein had the\nmaterials to produce as much as 500 tons of sarin, mustard, and VX nerve\nagent. In such quantities, these chemical agents also could kill untold\nthousands. He has not accounted for these materials. He has given no\nevidence that he has destroyed them.\n\nU.S. intelligence indicates that Saddam Hussein had upwards of 30,000\nmunitions capable of delivering chemical agents. Inspectors recently\nturned up 16 of them, despite Iraq's recent declaration denying their\nexistence. Saddam Hussein has not accounted for the remaining 29,984 of\nthese prohibited munitions. He has given no evidence that he has\ndestroyed them.\n\nFrom three Iraqi defectors we know that Iraq, in the late 1990s, had\nseveral mobile biological weapons labs. These are designed to produce\ngerm warfare agents, and can be moved from place to place to evade\ninspectors. Saddam Hussein has not disclosed these facilities. He has\ngiven no evidence that he has destroyed them.\n\nThe International Atomic Energy Agency confirmed in the 1990s that\nSaddam Hussein had an advanced nuclear weapons development program, had\na design for a nuclear weapon, and was working on five different methods\nof enriching uranium for a bomb. The British government has learned that\nSaddam Hussein recently sought significant quantities of uranium from\nAfrica. Our intelligence sources tell us that he has attempted to\npurchase high strength aluminum tubes suitable for nuclear weapons\nproduction. Saddam Hussein has not credibly explained these activities.\nHe clearly has much to hide.\n\nThe dictator of Iraq is not disarming. To the contrary, he is deceiving.\nFrom intelligence sources, we know, for instance, that thousands of\nIraqi security personnel are at work hiding documents and materials from\nthe UN inspectors - sanitizing inspection sites, and monitoring the\ninspectors themselves. Iraqi officials accompany the inspectors in order\nto intimidate witnesses. Iraq is blocking U-2 surveillance flights\nrequested by the United Nations. Iraqi intelligence officers are posing\nas the scientists inspectors are supposed to interview. Real scientists\nhave been coached by Iraqi officials on what to say. And intelligence\nsources indicate that Saddam Hussein has ordered that scientists who\ncooperate with UN inspectors in disarming Iraq will be killed, along\nwith their families.\n\nYear after year, Saddam Hussein has gone to elaborate lengths, spent\nenormous sums, taken great risks, to build and keep weapons of mass\ndestruction - but why? The only possible explanation, the only possible\nuse he could have for those weapons, is to dominate, intimidate, or\nattack. With nuclear arms or a full arsenal of chemical and biological\nweapons, Saddam Hussein could resume his ambitions of conquest in the\nMiddle East, and create deadly havoc in the region. And this Congress\nand the American people must recognize another threat. Evidence from\nintelligence sources, secret communications, and statements by people\nnow in custody, reveal that Saddam Hussein aids and protects terrorists,\nincluding members of al-Qaida. Secretly, and without fingerprints, he\ncould provide one of his hidden weapons to terrorists, or help them\ndevelop their own.\n\nBefore September 11, 2001, many in the world believed that Saddam\nHussein could be contained. But chemical agents and lethal viruses and\nshadowy terrorist networks are not easily contained. Imagine those 19\nhijackers with other weapons, and other plans - this time armed by\nSaddam Hussein. It would take just one vial, one canister, one crate\nslipped into this country to bring a day of horror like none we have\never known. We will do everything in our power to make sure that day\nnever comes.\n\nSome have said we must not act until the threat is imminent. Since when\nhave terrorists and tyrants announced their intentions, politely putting\nus on notice before they strike? If this threat is permitted to fully\nand suddenly emerge, all actions, all words, and all recriminations\nwould come too late. Trusting in the sanity and restraint of Saddam\nHussein is not a strategy, and it is not an option.\n\nThis dictator, who is assembling the world's most dangerous weapons, has\nalready used them on whole villages - leaving thousands of his own\ncitizens dead, blind, or disfigured. Iraqi refugees tell us how forced\nconfessions are obtained - by torturing children while their parents are\nmade to watch. International human rights groups have catalogued other\nmethods used in the torture chambers of Iraq: electric shock, burning\nwith hot irons, dripping acid on the skin, mutilation with electric\ndrills, cutting out tongues, and rape.\n\nIf this is not evil, then evil has no meaning. And tonight I have a\nmessage for the brave and oppressed people of Iraq: Your enemy is not\nsurrounding your country - your enemy is ruling your country. And the\nday he and his regime are removed from power will be the day of your\nliberation.\n\nThe world has waited 12 years for Iraq to disarm. America will not\naccept a serious and mounting threat to our country, our friends, and\nour allies. The United States will ask the UN Security Council to\nconvene on February 5th to consider the facts of Iraq's ongoing defiance\nof the world. Secretary of State Powell will present information and\nintelligence about Iraq's illegal weapons programs; its attempts to hide\nthose weapons from inspectors; and its links to terrorist groups. We\nwill consult, but let there be no misunderstanding: If Saddam Hussein\ndoes not fully disarm, for the safety of our people, and for the peace\nof the world, we will lead a coalition to disarm him.\n\nTonight I also have a message for the men and women who will keep the\npeace, members of the American Armed Forces: Many of you are assembling\nin and near the Middle East, and some crucial hours may lie ahead. In\nthose hours, the success of our cause will depend on you. Your training\nhas prepared you. Your honor will guide you. You believe in America, and\nAmerica believes in you.\n\nSending Americans into battle is the most profound decision a president\ncan make. The technologies of war have changed. The risks and suffering\nof war have not. For the brave Americans who bear the risk, no victory\nis free from sorrow. This Nation fights reluctantly, because we know the\ncost, and we dread the days of mourning that always come.\n\nWe seek peace. We strive for peace. And sometimes peace must be\ndefended. A future lived at the mercy of terrible threats is no peace at\nall. If war is forced upon us, we will fight in a just cause and by just\nmeans - sparing, in every way we can, the innocent. And if war is forced\nupon us, we will fight with the full force and might of the United\nStates military - and we will prevail. And as we and our coalition\npartners are doing in Afghanistan, we will bring to the Iraqi people\nfood, and medicines, and supplies...and freedom.\n\nMany challenges, abroad and at home, have arrived in a single season. In\ntwo years, America has gone from a sense of invulnerability to an\nawareness of peril...from bitter division in small matters to calm unity\nin great causes. And we go forward with confidence, because this call of\nhistory has come to the right country.\n\nAmericans are a resolute people, who have risen to every test of our\ntime. Adversity has revealed the character of our country, to the world,\nand to ourselves.\n\nAmerica is a strong Nation, and honorable in the use of our strength. We\nexercise power without conquest, and sacrifice for the liberty of\nstrangers.\n\n\nAmericans are a free people, who know that freedom is the right of every\nperson and the future of every nation. The liberty we prize is not\nAmerica's gift to the world, it is God;s gift to humanity.\n\nWe Americans have faith in ourselves - but not in ourselves alone. We do\nnot claim to know all the ways of Providence, yet we can trust in them,\nplacing our confidence in the loving God behind all of life, and all of\nhistory.\n\nMay He guide us now, and may God continue to bless the United States of\nAmerica.\n\nThank you.\n"

[1] "Mr. Speaker, Mr. Vice President, Members of Congress, distinguished\nguests, and fellow Americans: Tonight I want to begin by congratulating\nthe men and women of the 112th Congress, as well as your new Speaker,\nJohn Boehner. And as we mark this occasion, we're also mindful of the\nempty chair in this Chamber, and we pray for the health of our\ncolleague and our friend Gabby Giffords.\n\nIt's no secret that those of us here tonight have had our differences\nover the last 2 years. The debates have been contentious; we have\nfought fiercely for our beliefs. And that's a good thing. That's what a\nrobust democracy demands. That's what helps set us apart as a nation.\n\nBut there's a reason the tragedy in Tucson gave us pause. Amid all the\nnoise and passion and rancor of our public debate, Tucson reminded us\nthat no matter who we are or where we come from, each of us is a part\nof something greater, something more consequential than party or\npolitical preference.\n\nWe are part of the American family. We believe that in a country where\nevery race and faith and point of view can be found, we are still bound\ntogether as one people, that we share common hopes and a common creed,\nthat the dreams of a little girl in Tucson are not so different than\nthose of our own children, that they all deserve the chance to be\nfulfilled. That too is what sets us apart as a nation.\n\nNow, by itself, this simple recognition won't usher in a new era of\ncooperation. What comes of this moment is up to us. What comes of this\nmoment will be determined not by whether we can sit together tonight,\nbut whether we can work together tomorrow.\n\nI believe we can, and I believe we must. That's what the people who\nsent us here expect of us. With their votes, they've determined that\ngoverning will now be a shared responsibility between parties. New laws\nwill only pass with support from Democrats and Republicans. We will\nmove forward together or not at all, for the challenges we face are\nbigger than party and bigger than politics.\n\nAt stake right now is not who wins the next election. After all, we\njust had an election. At stake is whether new jobs and industries take\nroot in this country or somewhere else. It's whether the hard work and\nindustry of our people is rewarded. It's whether we sustain the\nleadership that has made America not just a place on a map, but the\nlight to the world.\n\nWe are poised for progress. Two years after the worst recession most of\nus have ever known, the stock market has come roaring back, corporate\nprofits are up, the economy is growing again.\n\nBut we have never measured progress by these yardsticks alone. We\nmeasure progress by the success of our people, by the jobs they can\nfind and the quality of life those jobs offer, by the prospects of a\nsmall-business owner who dreams of turning a good idea into a thriving\nenterprise, by the opportunities for a better life that we pass on to\nour children.\n\nThat's the project the American people want us to work on--together.\n\nNow, we did that in December. Thanks to the tax cuts we passed,\nAmericans' paychecks are a little bigger today. Every business can\nwrite off the full cost of new investments that they make this year.\nAnd these steps, taken by Democrats and Republicans, will grow the\neconomy and add to the more than 1 million private sector jobs created\nlast year.\n\nBut we have to do more. These steps we've taken over the last 2 years\nmay have broken the back of this recession, but to win the future,\nwe'll need to take on challenges that have been decades in the making.\n\nMany people watching tonight can probably remember a time when finding\na good job meant showing up at a nearby factory or a business downtown.\nYou didn't always need a degree, and your competition was pretty much\nlimited to your neighbors. If you worked hard, chances are you'd have a\njob for life, with a decent paycheck and good benefits and the\noccasional promotion. Maybe you'd even have the pride of seeing your\nkids work at the same company.\n\nThat world has changed. And for many, the change has been painful. I've\nseen it in the shuttered windows of once booming factories and the\nvacant storefronts on once busy Main Streets. I've heard it in the\nfrustrations of Americans who've seen their paychecks dwindle or their\njobs disappear, proud men and women who feel like the rules have been\nchanged in the middle of the game.\n\nThey're right. The rules have changed. In a single generation,\nrevolutions in technology have transformed the way we live, work, and\ndo business. Steel mills that once needed 1,000 workers can now do the\nsame work with 100. Today, just about any company can set up shop, hire\nworkers, and sell their products wherever there's an Internet\nconnection.\n\nMeanwhile, nations like China and India realized that with some changes\nof their own, they could compete in this new world. And so they started\neducating their children earlier and longer, with greater emphasis on\nmath and science. They're investing in research and new technologies.\nJust recently, China became the home to the world's largest private\nsolar research facility and the world's fastest computer.\n\nSo yes, the world is changed. The competition for jobs is real. But\nthis shouldn't discourage us. It should challenge us. Remember, for all\nthe hits we've taken these last few years, for all the naysayers\npredicting our decline, America still has the largest, most prosperous\neconomy in the world. No workers are more productive than ours. No\ncountry has more successful companies or grants more patents to\ninventors and entrepreneurs. We're the home to the world's best\ncolleges and universities, where more students come to study than any\nplace on Earth.\n\nWhat's more, we are the first nation to be founded for the sake of an\nidea: the idea that each of us deserves the chance to shape our own\ndestiny. That's why centuries of pioneers and immigrants have risked\neverything to come here. It's why our students don't just memorize\nequations, but answer questions like: \"What do you think of that idea?\nWhat would you change about the world? What do you want to be when you\ngrow up?\"\n\nThe future is ours to win. But to get there, we can't just stand still.\nAs Robert Kennedy told us: \"The future is not a gift. It is an\nachievement.\" Sustaining the American Dream has never been about\nstanding pat. It has required each generation to sacrifice and struggle\nand meet the demands of a new age.\n\nAnd now it's our turn. We know what it takes to compete for the jobs\nand industries of our time. We need to outinnovate, outeducate, and\noutbuild the rest of the world. We have to make America the best place\non Earth to do business. We need to take responsibility for our deficit\nand reform our Government. That's how our people will prosper. That's\nhow we'll win the future. And tonight I'd like to talk about how we get\nthere.\n\nThe first step in winning the future is encouraging American innovation.\nNone of us can predict with certainty what the next big industry will\nbe or where the new jobs will come from. Thirty years ago, we couldn't\nknow that something called the Internet would lead to an economic\nrevolution. What we can do--what America does better than anyone else--\nis spark the creativity and imagination of our people. We're the nation\nthat put cars in driveways and computers in offices; the nation of\nEdison and the Wright brothers, of Google and Facebook. In America,\ninnovation doesn't just change our lives. It is how we make our living.\n\nOur free enterprise system is what drives innovation. But because it's\nnot always profitable for companies to invest in basic research,\nthroughout our history, our Government has provided cutting-edge\nscientists and inventors with the support that they need. That's what\nplanted the seeds for the Internet. That's what helped make possible\nthings like computer chips and GPS. Just think of all the good jobs--\nfrom manufacturing to retail--that have come from these breakthroughs.\n\nHalf a century ago, when the Soviets beat us into space with the launch\nof a satellite called Sputnik, we had no idea how we would beat them to\nthe Moon. The science wasn't even there yet. NASA didn't exist. But\nafter investing in better research and education, we didn't just\nsurpass the Soviets, we unleashed a wave of innovation that created new\nindustries and millions of new jobs.\n\nThis is our generation's Sputnik moment. Two years ago, I said that we\nneeded to reach a level of research and development we haven't seen\nsince the height of the space race. And in a few weeks, I will be\nsending a budget to Congress that helps us meet that goal. We'll invest\nin biomedical research, information technology, and especially clean\nenergy technology, an investment that will strengthen our security,\nprotect our planet, and create countless new jobs for our people.\n\nAlready, we're seeing the promise of renewable energy. Robert and Gary\nAllen are brothers who run a small Michigan roofing company. After\nSeptember 11, they volunteered their best roofers to help repair the\nPentagon. But half of their factory went unused, and the recession hit\nthem hard. Today, with the help of a Government loan, that empty space\nis being used to manufacture solar shingles that are being sold all\nacross the country. In Robert's words, \"We reinvented ourselves.\"\n\nThat's what Americans have done for over 200 years: reinvented\nourselves. And to spur on more success stories like the Allen Brothers,\nwe've begun to reinvent our energy policy. We're not just handing out\nmoney. We're issuing a challenge. We're telling America's scientists\nand engineers that if they assemble teams of the best minds in their\nfields and focus on the hardest problems in clean energy, we'll fund\nthe Apollo projects of our time.\n\nAt the California Institute of Technology, they're developing a way to\nturn sunlight and water into fuel for our cars. At Oak Ridge National\nLaboratory, they're using supercomputers to get a lot more power out of\nour nuclear facilities. With more research and incentives, we can break\nour dependence on oil with biofuels and become the first country to\nhave a million electric vehicles on the road by 2015.\n\nWe need to get behind this innovation. And to help pay for it, I'm\nasking Congress to eliminate the billions in taxpayer dollars we\ncurrently give to oil companies. I don't know if you've noticed, but\nthey're doing just fine on their own. [Laughter] So instead of\nsubsidizing yesterday's energy, let's invest in tomorrow's.\n\nNow, clean energy breakthroughs will only translate into clean energy\njobs if businesses know there will be a market for what they're selling.\nSo tonight I challenge you to join me in setting a new goal: By 2035,\n80 percent of America's electricity will come from clean energy sources.\n\nSome folks want wind and solar. Others want nuclear, clean coal, and\nnatural gas. To meet this goal, we will need them all, and I urge\nDemocrats and Republicans to work together to make it happen.\n\nMaintaining our leadership in research and technology is crucial to\nAmerica's success. But if we want to win the future, if we want\ninnovation to produce jobs in America and not overseas, then we also\nhave to win the race to educate our kids.\n\nThink about it. Over the next 10 years, nearly half of all new jobs\nwill require education that goes beyond a high school education. And\nyet as many as a quarter of our students aren't even finishing high\nschool. The quality of our math and science education lags behind many\nother nations. America has fallen to ninth in the proportion of young\npeople with a college degree. And so the question is whether all of us,\nas citizens and as parents, are willing to do what's necessary to give\nevery child a chance to succeed.\n\nThat responsibility begins not in our classrooms, but in our homes and\ncommunities. It's family that first instills the love of learning in a\nchild. Only parents can make sure the TV is turned off and homework\ngets done. We need to teach our kids that it's not just the winner of\nthe Super Bowl who deserves to be celebrated, but the winner of the\nscience fair. We need to teach them that success is not a function of\nfame or PR, but of hard work and discipline.\n\nOur schools share this responsibility. When a child walks into a\nclassroom, it should be a place of high expectations and high\nperformance. But too many schools don't meet this test. That's why\ninstead of just pouring money into a system that's not working, we\nlaunched a competition called Race to the Top. To all 50 States, we\nsaid, \"If you show us the most innovative plans to improve teacher\nquality and student achievement, we'll show you the money.\"\n\nRace to the Top is the most meaningful reform of our public schools in\na generation. And these standards were developed, by the way,\nnot by Washington, but by Republican and Democratic Governors\nthroughout the country. We want to reward good teachers and stop making\nexcuses for bad ones. And over the next 10 years, with so many baby\nboomers retiring from our classrooms, we want to prepare 100,000 new\nteachers in the fields of science and technology and engineering and\nmath.\n\nIn fact, to every young person listening tonight who's contemplating\ntheir career choice: If you want to make a difference in the life of\nour Nation, if you want to make a difference in the life of a child,\nbecome a teacher. One mother of\ntwo, a woman named Kathy Proctor, had worked in the furniture industry\nsince she was 18 years old. As Kathy said, \"I hope it tells them to never give up.\"\n\nIf we take these steps, if we raise expectations for every child and\ngive them the best possible chance at an education, from the day they\nare born until the last job they take, we will reach the goal that I\nset 2 years ago: By the end of the decade, America will once again have\nthe highest proportion of college graduates in the world.\n\nOne last point about education: Today, there are hundreds of thousands\nof students excelling in our schools who are not American citizens.\nSome are the children of undocumented workers, who had nothing to do\nwith the actions of their parents. It can be done.\n\nTo help businesses sell more products abroad, we set a goal of doubling\nour exports by 2014. Because the more we export, the more jobs we\ncreate here at home. [1] "Thank you. Mr. Speaker, Mr. Vice President, Members of Congress, my\nfellow Americans: Tonight marks the eighth year that I've come here to\nreport on the State of the Union. And for this final one, I'm going to\ntry to make it a little shorter. I know some of you are antsy to get\nback to Iowa. [Laughter] I've been there. I'll be shaking hands\nafterwards if you want some tips. [Laughter]\n\nNow, I understand that because it's an election season, expectations\nfor what we will achieve this year are low. But, Mr. Speaker, I\nappreciate the constructive approach that you and other leaders took at\nthe end of last year to pass a budget and make tax cuts permanent for\nworking families. So I hope we can work together this year on some\nbipartisan priorities like criminal justice reform and helping people\nwho are battling prescription drug abuse and heroin abuse. So, who\nknows, we might surprise the cynics again.\n\nBut tonight I want to go easy on the traditional list of proposals for\nthe year ahead. Don't worry, I've got plenty--[laughter]--from helping\nstudents learn to write computer code to personalizing medical\ntreatments for patients. And I will keep pushing for progress on the\nwork that I believe still needs to be done: fixing a broken immigration\nsystem, protecting our kids from gun violence, equal pay for equal work,\npaid leave, raising the minimum wage. All these things still matter to\nhard-working families. They're still the right thing to do. And I won't\nlet up until they get done.\n\nBut for my final address to this Chamber, I don't want to just talk\nabout next year. I want to focus on the next 5 years, the next 10 years,\nand beyond. I want to focus on our future.\n\nWe live in a time of extraordinary change, change that's reshaping the\nway we live, the way we work, our planet, our place in the world. It's\nchange that promises amazing medical breakthroughs, but also economic\ndisruptions that strain working families. It promises this education\nfor girls in the most remote villages, but also connects terrorists\nplotting an ocean away. It's change that can broaden opportunity or\nwiden inequality. And whether we like it or not, the pace of this\nchange will only accelerate.\n\nAmerica has been through big changes before: wars and depression, the\ninflux of new immigrants, workers fighting for a fair deal, movements\nto expand civil rights. Each time, there have been those who told us to\nfear the future; who claimed we could slam the brakes on change; who\npromised to restore past glory if we just got some group or idea that\nwas threatening America under control. And each time, we overcame those\nfears. We did not, in the words of Lincoln, adhere to the \"dogmas of\nthe quiet past.\" Instead, we thought anew and acted anew. We made\nchange work for us, always extending America's promise outward, to the\nnext frontier, to more people. And because we did, because we saw\nopportunity with a--where others saw peril, we emerged stronger and\nbetter than before.\n\nWhat was true then can be true now. Our unique strengths as a nation--\nour optimism and work ethic, our spirit of discovery, our diversity,\nour commitment to rule of law--these things give us everything we need\nto ensure prosperity and security for generations to come.\n\nIn fact, it's in that spirit that we have made progress these past 7\nyears. That's how we recovered from the worst economic crisis in\ngenerations. That's how we reformed our health care system and\nreinvented our energy sector. That's how we delivered more care and\nbenefits to our troops coming home and our veterans. That's how we\nsecured the freedom in every State to marry the person we love.\n\nBut such progress is not inevitable. It's the result of choices we make\ntogether. And we face such choices right now. Will we respond to the\nchanges of our time with fear, turning inward as a nation, turning\nagainst each other as a people?
